:: Act1 09b Rowan Finds Vesper
<h1>Optional 09b: Rowan Finds Vesper</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 09b_rowan_finds_vesper.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **LUMEN THIEF - PRIVATE NOTE (VESPER):** &gt; *Topic: where the name came from* &gt; *Reminder: love can be a discipline*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The rook sits on Vesper&#x27;s desk like it&#x27;s waiting for a verdict.]</p>
<p>[Dark wood. Worn edges. The kind of object that looks small until you realize someone carried it for years.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna notices it because she notices everything that might be a rule.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] What&#x27;s that.</p>
<p>[Vesper doesn&#x27;t look up from the identity paperwork.]</p>
<p>Vesper: A rook.</p>
<p>Avyanna: I know. Why.</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s pen stops.]</p>
<p>[A breath. Controlled. Like she&#x27;s deciding whether this answer is safe to give a sixteen-year-old.]</p>
<p>Vesper: It was a gift.</p>
<p>[Avyanna waits. The ship taught her that waiting isn&#x27;t always punishment.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Rowan gave it to me.</p>
<p>[The name lands with weight. Not because Avyanna knows Rowan, but because Vesper&#x27;s voice shifts when she says it-fractionally older, fractionally more careful.]</p>
<p>(Rowan.)</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s thumb brushes the rook like it&#x27;s a scar you can touch without bleeding.]</p>
<hr>
<p>## Intercut - Twelve (Rowan&#x27;s First Lesson)</p>
<p>[The station&#x27;s arbitration hall smells like paper and fear.]</p>
<p>[Not the clean fear of violence.]</p>
<p>[The slow fear of being decided about by strangers.]</p>
<p>[Vesper stands behind a broker in a suit that costs more than her childhood did.]</p>
<p>[She is twelve and already good at being invisible when it serves someone else.]</p>
<p>[The broker is talking like he&#x27;s telling the truth. He isn&#x27;t.]</p>
<p>[Vesper can feel the lie in the cadence-where he speeds up, where he slows down, where he uses a word that sounds neutral but isn&#x27;t.]</p>
<p>Broker: ...standard withholding. Standard jurisdiction. Standard-</p>
<p>[&quot;Standard&quot; is a spell. Vesper hears it like one.]</p>
<p>[Across the hall, a woman watches.]</p>
<p>[Older. Not old. The kind of older that makes rooms rearrange themselves so she can pass through.]</p>
<p>[She isn&#x27;t wearing a badge.]</p>
<p>[She doesn&#x27;t need one.]</p>
<p>[She has someone else&#x27;s confidence, worn like a coat.]</p>
<p>[Rowan Rook.]</p>
<p>[Vesper doesn&#x27;t know her name yet.]</p>
<p>[She just knows the woman is looking at the same lie and not flinching.]</p>
<p>[The broker&#x27;s opponent-a labor representative with cracked nails-starts to fold.]</p>
<p>Labor Rep: If we just adjust the rate a little, maybe-</p>
<p>[The broker smiles. Gentle. Predatory.]</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s stomach tightens.]</p>
<p>(If they adjust, the math still kills them. It just kills them slower.)</p>
<p>[Vesper leans in and whispers to the broker-quiet enough no one can accuse her of speaking out of turn.]</p>
<p>Vesper: If you concede now, they&#x27;ll raise the compliance fee in two weeks. They always do. It&#x27;s in the supplemental schedule.</p>
<p>[The broker&#x27;s jaw tightens. He ignores her.]</p>
<p>[Because she&#x27;s the assistant.]</p>
<p>[Because she&#x27;s a tool.]</p>
<p>[Because tools don&#x27;t get to have opinions.]</p>
<p>[Rowan Rook stands up.]</p>
<p>[Not dramatic.]</p>
<p>[Just... standing, and suddenly the air has a spine.]</p>
<p>Rowan: Objection.</p>
<p>[A murmur ripples through the hall. The arbitrator blinks like he forgot people could interrupt procedure.]</p>
<p>Arbitrator: On what basis.</p>
<p>Rowan: On the basis that you are being asked to bless a murder with paperwork.</p>
<p>[Silence.]</p>
<p>[The broker turns, incredulous.]</p>
<p>Broker: Who are you.</p>
<p>Rowan: [mild] Someone who reads.</p>
<p>[Rowan&#x27;s gaze flicks to Vesper for half a second.]</p>
<p>[Not pity.]</p>
<p>[Recognition.]</p>
<p>[Rowan speaks like she&#x27;s talking to the whole room, but the words land like they&#x27;re aimed at one girl behind a liar.]</p>
<p>Rowan: &quot;Standard&quot; is a story people tell so they don&#x27;t have to admit they are choosing harm.</p>
<p>Rowan: Show the full schedule. Not the summary. Not the highlight reel. The full ledger.</p>
<p>[The arbitrator hesitates.]</p>
<p>[Rowan waits. Patient. Not begging. Not threatening.]</p>
<p>[Just making the truth heavy enough that refusing it would require effort.]</p>
<p>[The labor representative lifts their chin.]</p>
<p>Labor Rep: We have it.</p>
<p>[They slide a document forward. Paper. Physical. Court-proof.]</p>
<p>[The broker&#x27;s smile cracks.]</p>
<p>[Rowan&#x27;s mouth twitches like she&#x27;s pleased and annoyed at once.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[After, the broker storms out.]</p>
<p>[Vesper follows automatically, still in assistant posture, still trained to chase whoever pays her oxygen.]</p>
<p>[Rowan steps into her path in the corridor.]</p>
<p>Rowan: You saw it.</p>
<p>[Vesper freezes.]</p>
<p>[No one has ever asked her if she &quot;saw&quot; something like it mattered.]</p>
<p>Vesper: I did.</p>
<p>Rowan: You didn&#x27;t speak.</p>
<p>Vesper: I&#x27;m not allowed to.</p>
<p>Rowan: That&#x27;s an excuse.</p>
<p>[The words should feel like a slap.]</p>
<p>[They don&#x27;t.]</p>
<p>[They feel like a door unlocking.]</p>
<p>Rowan: You want to be useful.</p>
<p>Vesper: Yes.</p>
<p>Rowan: Then be honest about your constraints.</p>
<p>Rowan: If you can&#x27;t speak, you find a way to make the truth speak without you.</p>
<p>[Rowan reaches into her pocket and pulls out a small carved rook.]</p>
<p>[Sets it on the corridor rail between them.]</p>
<p>Rowan: Do you know what this is.</p>
<p>Vesper: A chess piece.</p>
<p>Rowan: It&#x27;s an exit.</p>
<p>[Vesper frowns.]</p>
<p>Rowan: The rook moves straight.</p>
<p>Rowan: No diagonals. No flourish. No pleading.</p>
<p>Rowan: When you want something in a room full of liars, you move straight toward it.</p>
<p>Rowan: And you accept the cost of being seen.</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Why are you telling me this.</p>
<p>Rowan: Because you&#x27;re already doing the first part.</p>
<p>Rowan: You&#x27;re seeing.</p>
<p>Rowan: I&#x27;m offering you the second part.</p>
<p>[Rowan&#x27;s hand hovers over the rook, then pulls back.]</p>
<p>[Not taking. Not insisting. Offering.]</p>
<p>Rowan: You can refuse.</p>
<p>Rowan: No penalty.</p>
<p>[Vesper stares at the rook.]</p>
<p>(Refusal without punishment. That&#x27;s not a thing.)</p>
<p>[Rowan waits anyway, like she means it.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [quiet] What do you want from me.</p>
<p>Rowan: Nothing you can&#x27;t give freely.</p>
<p>Rowan: I want you to stop letting people use your competence like it belongs to them.</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s chest hurts with something sharp and unfamiliar.]</p>
<p>Vesper: I don&#x27;t have a place.</p>
<p>Rowan: Then take one.</p>
<p>Rowan: Or come with me and we&#x27;ll build one.</p>
<p>[Vesper reaches for the rook.]</p>
<p>[Her fingers tremble once.]</p>
<p>[Then steady.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Okay.</p>
<p>[Rowan nods like she expected it, but still respects that it was chosen.]</p>
<p>Rowan: Good.</p>
<p>Rowan: First lesson, then.</p>
<p>Rowan: Love can be a discipline.</p>
<p>Rowan: Not a hunger.</p>
<p>[Vesper doesn&#x27;t understand yet.]</p>
<p>[But she keeps the rook.]</p>
<p>[And for the next six years, Rowan will teach her what that means-raising her without owning her, protecting her without possession, loving her without crossing lines that can&#x27;t be uncrossed.]</p>
<p>[When Vesper turns eighteen, Rowan will look at her across a table and say: &quot;Now you get to choose.&quot;]</p>
<p>[And Vesper will choose her. Freely. Equally. Without the weight of debt or dependency pressing down on the answer.]</p>
<p>[Three years after that, Rowan will die protecting her one last time. And Vesper will carry the rook-and the lesson-forward into every negotiation, every contract, every moment when power and care threaten to collapse into the same terrible thing.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Back in the present, Vesper&#x27;s pen moves again.]</p>
<p>[The rook sits under her palm like a held line.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [careful] Do you miss her.</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s throat works.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Yes.</p>
<p>[A beat.]</p>
<p>Vesper: And I don&#x27;t use that to make you smaller.</p>
<p>[Avyanna swallows.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Okay.</p>
<p>[Vesper returns to the paperwork.]</p>
<p>[But she leaves the rook where Avyanna can see it.]</p>
</div>

