:: Act1 11a Id Names Forms
<h1>Optional 11a: Id Names Forms</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 11a_id_names_forms.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS BETWEEN CH11-12]** &gt; *Location: Lumen Thief secure conference room* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Vesper, Elisira* &gt; *Teaching: Identity systems, paperwork as weapon, harm reduction through documentation*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The conference room is smaller than Avyanna expected. One table, three chairs, a secure terminal, and walls that Cinnamon assures her are soundproofed.]</p>
<p>[Vesper sits with three different datapads arranged in front of her like cards in a game. Elisira stands near the door-not blocking it, just present.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna sits across from Vesper and tries not to look like she&#x27;s calculating exits.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [calm] We&#x27;re going to register you properly. Three systems. Three different identities. All legitimate. All protective.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [confused] Three?</p>
<p>Elisira: [from the door] Some people need five names to survive. Three is conservative.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper taps the first datapad.]</p>
<p>Vesper: System one: Rim Accord. This is your primary legal identity. The one that says you&#x27;re a free citizen with full autonomy. No indenture contracts. No ownership claims. No extraction permissions.</p>
<p>[She pulls up a form. It&#x27;s written in plain language-none of the labyrinthine jargon Avyanna remembers from the mine&#x27;s paperwork.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Name, birthdate, origin station, current residence, occupation. Standard fields. But here&#x27;s what matters: every piece of information you put here is public record. Anyone can request it. Compact, Guild, random busybody with a credit chit.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [tense] So they can find me.</p>
<p>Vesper: [precise] They can find this version of you. Which is why we&#x27;re strategic about what this version says.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper walks through each field.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Name. You&#x27;re using Avyanna Lagrange. That&#x27;s your choice. If you wanted to change it, now&#x27;s the time.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] I want to keep it. It&#x27;s... mine.</p>
<p>Vesper: [nodding] Understood. Birthdate. The mine didn&#x27;t track yours. So you pick one. Any date. It&#x27;s yours now.</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the calendar field.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I don&#x27;t... how do I choose?</p>
<p>Elisira: [dryly] Pick a date that makes you hard to profile. Not a holiday. Not a memorable anniversary. Something ordinary.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [after a moment] Third month, fourteenth day. Standard year... I don&#x27;t know. Seventeen years ago?</p>
<p>Vesper: [entering it] Close enough. We&#x27;ll backdate your age to seventeen. Young enough that gaps in your record are explainable, old enough that you have legal autonomy.</p>
<hr>
<p>Vesper: Origin station. This one&#x27;s strategic. We&#x27;re not listing Aurum Extraction. We&#x27;re listing Taelios Forge-a mid-tier manufacturing station with lousy record-keeping. If anyone checks, the station will shrug and say &quot;records incomplete due to fire in archive seven years ago.&quot;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slowly] You&#x27;re... lying?</p>
<p>Vesper: [meeting her eyes] I&#x27;m protecting you with plausible deniability. Taelios is real. The fire is real. Your presence there is unfalsifiable because the records genuinely don&#x27;t exist.</p>
<p>Elisira: [adding] This is harm reduction. We&#x27;re giving you a past that doesn&#x27;t make you a target.</p>
<hr>
<p>Vesper: Current residence: Lumen Thief, Guild registry 7742-KAEL. Occupation: apprentice evidence contractor.</p>
<p>[She pauses.]</p>
<p>Vesper: That last one is important. &quot;Apprentice&quot; means you&#x27;re learning, not experienced. Keeps expectations low. &quot;Evidence contractor&quot; means you work with the Guild but aren&#x27;t Guild property. You&#x27;re crew, not asset.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [testing the words] Crew. Not asset.</p>
<p>Vesper: [firm] Crew. With full autonomy. This form makes that official.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper taps through the rest of the fields. Medical information: minimal disclosure. Education: &quot;station standard, records incomplete.&quot; Emergency contacts: Lumen Thief crew roster.]</p>
<p>[She submits the form. A confirmation code appears.]</p>
<p>Vesper: That&#x27;s identity one. Rim Accord now recognizes you as a free citizen. If anyone questions your status, you show them this registry number. It&#x27;s your proof of autonomy.</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the number. Seventeen characters. Hers.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper switches to the second datapad.]</p>
<p>Vesper: System two: Guild transit credentials. This one&#x27;s more restricted. Only Guild-affiliated stations can access it. But it gives you freedom of movement on Guild routes without customs hassles.</p>
<p>[Another form. This one asks for biometrics.]</p>
<p>Vesper: We&#x27;ll need a retinal scan, fingerprints, and a voiceprint. All stored encrypted. Only released to Guild checkpoints, and only when you authorize it.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [wary] What if I don&#x27;t authorize it?</p>
<p>Vesper: Then you don&#x27;t get through the checkpoint. But that&#x27;s your choice. You control when your biometrics are shared.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Elisira steps forward with a small scanner.]</p>
<p>Elisira: This won&#x27;t hurt. Look here. Don&#x27;t blink.</p>
<p>[Flash. Avyanna&#x27;s retina captured in a quarter-second. Fingerprints next-each finger pressed to a cool glass surface. Then voiceprint: Avyanna speaks her name, her registry number, and a randomized passphrase.]</p>
<p>[All of it stored. All of it hers. All of it controlled by her consent.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [submitting] Guild transit credentials issued. You can now move through Guild space with minimal friction.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper picks up the third datapad. Pauses.]</p>
<p>Vesper: System three is different. This one is... insurance.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [sensing weight] Insurance?</p>
<p>Vesper: [carefully] Some people need a name that isn&#x27;t connected to their primary identity. A name they can use when the first two are compromised. A name that lets them disappear if necessary.</p>
<p>Elisira: [from the door] We call it an egress identity. A way out when the walls close in.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s stomach tightens.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: You think I&#x27;ll need to disappear?</p>
<p>Vesper: [honest] I think you might. The Compact knows you exist. Aurum Extraction knows you exist. Right now, they don&#x27;t know where you are. But if they find out, you&#x27;ll need options.</p>
<p>[She slides the third datapad across the table.]</p>
<p>Vesper: This identity is minimal. Different name. Different birthdate. Different origin. Same species, same approximate age, but everything else is fiction. We&#x27;ll register it with a neutral station that doesn&#x27;t share data automatically.</p>
<p>Vesper: You&#x27;ll never use it unless you have to. But if you need it, it&#x27;ll be there.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the blank form.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: What name do I use?</p>
<p>Vesper: Your choice. Pick something that doesn&#x27;t emotionally attach to you. This identity is a tool, not a person.</p>
<p>[Avyanna thinks. Names from the mine. Names from stations she&#x27;s seen. Something ordinary. Something forgettable.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slowly] Kess Tam.</p>
<p>Vesper: [approving] Good. Generic. Unremarkable. Birthdate?</p>
<p>Avyanna: Eighth month, second day. Eighteen years ago.</p>
<p>Vesper: Origin?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [looking at Vesper] You choose. I don&#x27;t know what&#x27;s safe.</p>
<p>Vesper: [noting] Miren&#x27;s Cradle. Agricultural station. Large population, high turnover, minimal surveillance. Perfect for ghosts.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They fill out the rest. Minimal details. No medical history. No education records. No emergency contacts. Just a name, a face, and a birthdate that might exist somewhere in the statistical noise of the galaxy.]</p>
<p>[Vesper submits it. Another confirmation code. Another identity, stored and waiting.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [meeting Avyanna&#x27;s eyes] You now have three names. Three versions of yourself, each with different utility and different exposure.</p>
<p>Vesper: Avyanna Lagrange, Rim Accord citizen: this is who you are publicly.</p>
<p>Vesper: Avyanna Lagrange, Guild contractor: this is who you are professionally.</p>
<p>Vesper: Kess Tam: this is who you become if everything else fails.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands are shaking. Three names. Three lives. Three ways to exist.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [whispered] How do I remember which one to use?</p>
<p>Elisira: [stepping forward] Practice. We&#x27;ll drill scenarios. &quot;You&#x27;re at a Rim station, customs asks for ID&quot;-you show Rim Accord. &quot;You&#x27;re at a Guild checkpoint&quot;-you show Guild credentials. &quot;You&#x27;re running and someone&#x27;s hunting you&quot;-you become Kess Tam and you don&#x27;t look back.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper closes the datapads.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Now the hard part. Learning what information you&#x27;re willing to make public, and what you protect.</p>
<p>[She pulls up a sample form-a station customs declaration.]</p>
<p>Vesper: This form asks: name, origin, destination, purpose of visit, duration of stay, and &quot;any goods to declare.&quot;</p>
<p>[She taps each field.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Name: you give them your public identity. Avyanna Lagrange.</p>
<p>Vesper: Origin: you say &quot;Lumen Thief, Guild registry 7742-KAEL.&quot; You don&#x27;t elaborate.</p>
<p>Vesper: Destination: you tell them the station name. You don&#x27;t tell them who you&#x27;re visiting or why.</p>
<p>Vesper: Purpose: you say &quot;transit&quot; or &quot;Guild contract work.&quot; You don&#x27;t give specifics.</p>
<p>Vesper: Duration: you estimate conservatively. You don&#x27;t commit to leaving by a date.</p>
<p>Vesper: Goods: you declare what&#x27;s required by law. You don&#x27;t volunteer information.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna absorbs this.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slow] You&#x27;re teaching me to... give the minimum?</p>
<p>Vesper: [precise] I&#x27;m teaching you that you&#x27;re not required to tell strangers your life story. Information is leverage. Don&#x27;t hand it out for free.</p>
<p>[She pulls up another form-this one from a Compact administrative office.]</p>
<p>Vesper: This one asks: &quot;Are you now or have you ever been employed by an extraction facility?&quot;</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s breath catches.]</p>
<p>Vesper: What do you say?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking] I... was. In the mine.</p>
<p>Vesper: [gently] That&#x27;s the truth. But truth has nuance. You were *held* by an extraction facility. You were not employed-you were enslaved. The word &quot;employed&quot; implies consent, compensation, and autonomy. You had none of those.</p>
<p>Vesper: So the accurate answer is: &quot;No. I was held against my will by Aurum Extraction. I was never an employee.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the form.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] They&#x27;ll say I&#x27;m lying.</p>
<p>Vesper: [flat] Let them. Your answer is defensible. You&#x27;re reframing their language to reflect reality. That&#x27;s not lying-that&#x27;s refusing to adopt their narrative.</p>
<p>Elisira: [adding] And if they push, you say: &quot;That&#x27;s not your business. Next question.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p>[They practice. Twenty forms. Twenty scenarios. Each one designed to teach Avyanna what information is required, what&#x27;s optional, and what&#x27;s none of anyone&#x27;s damn business.]</p>
<p>**Scenario: Station Security** - Form asks: &quot;List all previous residences for the past five years.&quot; - Avyanna: [using the script] &quot;I was held at Aurum Extraction under indenture. I have no other residences to report.&quot; - Vesper: Good. You answered truthfully without giving them ammunition.</p>
<p>**Scenario: Medical Intake** - Form asks: &quot;Describe any pre-existing conditions or injuries.&quot; - Avyanna: [using the script] &quot;I&#x27;ll discuss that with my doctor. Not with your intake form.&quot; - Vesper: Correct. Medical history is between you and your provider. Intake forms don&#x27;t get access.</p>
<p>**Scenario: Banking** - Form asks: &quot;Source of funds?&quot; - Avyanna: [using the script] &quot;Wages from Guild contract work.&quot; - Vesper: Perfect. Accurate, minimal, unremarkable.</p>
<hr>
<p>[After an hour, Avyanna is exhausted. But something in her posture has shifted. She&#x27;s learning to hold boundaries in bureaucratic spaces.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [standing] Last lesson. The most important one.</p>
<p>[She pulls up a form. This one is from a Compact regulatory office.]</p>
<p>Vesper: This form asks you to &quot;voluntarily disclose&quot; information about Primordial Lattice interactions. It&#x27;s phrased like a survey. It&#x27;s actually a registry of people the Compact wants to track.</p>
<p>[She deletes the form without filling it out.]</p>
<p>Vesper: You never fill out &quot;voluntary disclosure&quot; forms. Ever. If disclosure is truly voluntary, you volunteer to decline.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna nods slowly.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: What if they say it&#x27;s required?</p>
<p>Vesper: [precise] Then you ask: &quot;Required by which law? Under which jurisdiction? Enforced by whom?&quot;</p>
<p>[She taps the table.]</p>
<p>Vesper: If they can&#x27;t answer all three, it&#x27;s not required. It&#x27;s a request dressed up as a mandate. And you decline.</p>
<p>Elisira: [adding] And if they try to coerce you-if they threaten consequences for declining-you document it and you report it. Because that&#x27;s not law. That&#x27;s extortion.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna sits back. Three identities. Boundaries in forms. Scripts for refusal.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] You&#x27;re teaching me to hide.</p>
<p>Vesper: [correcting] I&#x27;m teaching you to control what people know about you. There&#x27;s a difference between hiding and exercising informational autonomy.</p>
<p>Vesper: You&#x27;re not erasing yourself. You&#x27;re deciding which version of yourself is appropriate for which context.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna processes that.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: The mine wanted me to have no privacy. No secrets. No control over my own information.</p>
<p>Vesper: [nodding] Yes. Because control over information is power. They wanted all the power. We&#x27;re giving it back to you.</p>
<p>[She hands Avyanna a small data chip.]</p>
<p>Vesper: These are your credentials. All three identities, encrypted. Keep it on you. Memorize the access codes. If you ever need to use Kess Tam, you&#x27;ll have everything you need.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna takes the chip. It&#x27;s small. Lighter than it should be for the weight it carries.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [looking at Vesper] Have you ever had to use... an egress identity?</p>
<p>Vesper: [after a pause] Yes. Twice.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Did it work?</p>
<p>Vesper: [quietly] I&#x27;m still here.</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// IDENTITY SYSTEMS UPDATED: three registries established | RIM ACCORD: confirmed | GUILD TRANSIT: confirmed | EGRESS IDENTITY: stored encrypted | AUTONOMY: enhanced&gt;</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: trainee now has legal protections and exit strategies | ASSESSMENT: survivability increased | EMOTIONAL STATE: overwhelmed but processing | STATUS: this is good work&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Scene*</p>
</div>

