:: Act1 13a Starmap Hobby
<h1>Optional 13a: Starmap Hobby</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 13a_starmap_hobby.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[MICRO-SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH13, LIKELY SHIP&#x27;S EVENING]** &gt; *Location: Lumen Thief navigation alcove* &gt; *Present: Jalen, Avyanna* &gt; *Teaching: Constellation naming, pattern recognition, early shard-sense hints*</p>
<hr>
<p>[Evening cycle. The Lumen Thief&#x27;s navigation alcove is dim except for the star display-holographic projections overlaid on real-time sensor feeds. Jalen sits at the console, updating route calculations. Avyanna hovers near the doorway, uncertain whether she&#x27;s intruding.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [not looking up] You can come in.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [stepping forward] I didn&#x27;t want to interrupt.</p>
<p>Jalen: Navigation doesn&#x27;t mind witnesses. Sit.</p>
<p>[She settles onto the jump seat beside the console. The star display rotates slowly-hundreds of labeled points, trade routes marked in faint lines, hazard zones shaded in warning colors.]</p>
<p>[The shard at the base of her skull pulses. Gentle. Curious.]</p>
<hr>
<p>Avyanna: Earlier, when we were calibrating sensors... I said I didn&#x27;t know the constellation names.</p>
<p>Jalen: [glancing at her] Most people don&#x27;t. Not the real ones, anyway.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Real ones?</p>
<p>Jalen: [gesturing at the display] Every culture names the stars. Compact names, Guild names, local names. Sometimes the same cluster has six different designations depending on who&#x27;s claiming it.</p>
<p>[They tap a control. The labels shift-same stars, different text.]</p>
<p>Jalen: See? One set is pure sector code. One set is corridor shorthand. One set is whatever the locals decided was worth remembering.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [leaning forward] Why so many names?</p>
<p>Jalen: Because names aren&#x27;t just labels. They&#x27;re claims. &quot;I named this, therefore I know it, therefore it&#x27;s mine.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna studies the display. The shard pulses again-still gentle, but insistent. Like it&#x27;s trying to show her something.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] Can you teach me? Not the politics. Just... I want handles. Ways to remember where things are.</p>
<p>Jalen: [considering her] Most people learn navigation for work. You asking because you&#x27;re curious?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] In the mine, I never saw the stars. Didn&#x27;t know there were this many. Didn&#x27;t know they had names, or that names could be... complicated.</p>
<p>[She touches the edge of the display. Her fingers pass through a projected cluster.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I want to understand the map. Even if the map lies sometimes.</p>
<p>Jalen: [after a beat] That&#x27;s a good reason.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They adjust the display. Zoom out. The galactic arm spreads before them-a sweep of light and void.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Start with navigation-practical handles. The ones that matter for orientation, not ownership.</p>
<p>[They point to a bright cluster near the center of the display.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Four stars in a rough square. No matter where you are in this arm, if you can find that shape, you can get your bearings: coreward, rimward, up, down.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [committing it to memory] Square. Coreward.</p>
<p>Jalen: Good. Now this one-</p>
<p>[They highlight another formation. Three stars in a tight triangle, with a dimmer fourth trailing behind.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Triangle and a tail. It points relative to the plane. Helps you orient vertical when sensors are compromised.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They work through the practical constellations. Jalen is patient, methodical. Avyanna listens, focused, absorbing the patterns.]</p>
<p>[The shard continues to pulse. And then, as Jalen highlights a particular cluster near the edge of the display, something shifts.]</p>
<p>[The stars feel different. Not visually-she&#x27;s still seeing the same holographic projection. But underneath the image, there&#x27;s a... texture. A sense of presence. The cluster feels warm, somehow. Active. Like something is paying attention to it.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [blinking] That one feels-</p>
<p>[She stops. Tries to articulate what she just perceived. Fails.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [frustrated] Never mind. It&#x27;s nothing.</p>
<p>Jalen: [sharp] Don&#x27;t do that. If you noticed something, say it. Navigation is pattern recognition. Weird patterns are data.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna hesitates. Then tries again.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: That cluster. The one you just highlighted. It feels... different. Not bad different. Just-</p>
<p>[She touches the base of her skull, where the shard sits.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: It feels like something&#x27;s there. Not a ship. Not a station. Something else.</p>
<p>Jalen: [leaning back, studying her] Different how? Temperature? Pressure? Visual?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [struggling] None of those. It&#x27;s like... like the difference between a room with people in it and a room that&#x27;s empty. You can&#x27;t see them, but you know.</p>
<p>[Jalen pulls up sensor data for that cluster. Scans it. Frowns.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Nothing on sensors. No anomalies. Standard stellar activity.</p>
<p>[They look at Avyanna. Thoughtful.]</p>
<p>Jalen: But you&#x27;re not looking at sensors, are you?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [uncertain] I don&#x27;t know what I&#x27;m looking at.</p>
<hr>
<p>Jalen: [making a note on their tablet] Tell me when it happens again. If you feel something the sensors don&#x27;t show, I want to know.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [defensive] I&#x27;m not making it up-</p>
<p>Jalen: [cutting her off] I know. But perception is subjective, and subjective data is still data. If you&#x27;re sensing something I can&#x27;t, that&#x27;s worth tracking.</p>
<p>[They adjust the display again. Rotate through different star fields.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Look at these. Tell me if any of them feel &quot;different.&quot;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna focuses. The shard hums, cooperating now. It&#x27;s interested in this game.]</p>
<p>[Most of the stars feel neutral. Background. Ordinary.]</p>
<p>[But one cluster-a dense formation near a nebula-has that same presence. That same sense of occupied attention.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [pointing] That one.</p>
<p>[Jalen checks the coordinates. Makes another note.]</p>
<p>Jalen: Heavy Primordial signature. Low overlay clutter.</p>
<p>[They look at Avyanna with something like approval.]</p>
<p>Jalen: You&#x27;re sensing Lattice topology. The shard&#x27;s giving you perceptual texture that standard sensors don&#x27;t pick up.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slow] Is that... normal? For shard carriers?</p>
<p>Jalen: [dry] I don&#x27;t know. You&#x27;re the first one I&#x27;ve met.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They continue the lesson. Jalen teaches her the navigation-practical constellations. Avyanna learns the names, commits the patterns to memory.]</p>
<p>[But underneath the lesson, she&#x27;s learning something else: the shard isn&#x27;t just communicating with her. It&#x27;s changing how she perceives reality. Giving her information that doesn&#x27;t fit into visual, auditory, or tactile categories.]</p>
<p>[The galaxy has texture now. Presence. Topology.]</p>
<p>[And she doesn&#x27;t know yet if that&#x27;s a gift or a warning.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Later, when Avyanna leaves the alcove, Jalen writes a note in their personal log:]</p>
<p>&gt; *Trainee reports perceptual anomalies correlated with heavy Primordial signatures. Consistent with Nyx&#x27;s stated shard characteristics, but timeline unclear. Worth monitoring. Flagging for Nyx.*</p>
<p>[And then, in smaller text beneath:]</p>
<p>&gt; *She asked good questions. Wanted handles, not propaganda. Noticed when names were claims.* &gt; &gt; *Reminds me of someone. In a good way.*</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Micro-Scene*</p>
</div>

