:: Act1 13b Coffee Ritual
<h1>Optional 13b: Coffee Ritual</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 13b_coffee_ritual.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH13, EARLY MORNING]** &gt; *Location: Lumen Thief galley* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Rho, Jalen* &gt; *Purpose: Domestic routine, belonging without performance*</p>
<hr>
<p>[0530 ship time. The galley is dim except for the work lights over the counter.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna wakes early because she still doesn&#x27;t know how to sleep past dawn. The mine taught her that sleeping late meant missing rations. The Lumen Thief has no such rule, but her body doesn&#x27;t believe it yet.]</p>
<p>[She enters the galley expecting it to be empty.]</p>
<p>[It&#x27;s not.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho stands at the counter with his back to the door, doing something that involves the coffee maker, cursing, and what sounds like percussive maintenance.]</p>
<p>[Jalen sits at the table with a datapad, not looking up, radiating the particular stillness of someone who&#x27;s been awake for hours and plans to stay that way.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna freezes in the doorway.]</p>
<p>Rho: [not turning around] Come in or don&#x27;t. Door&#x27;s open either way.</p>
<p>[Avyanna steps in. The door hisses closed behind her.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho is making coffee. Badly. The machine hisses and spits like it&#x27;s personally offended.]</p>
<p>Rho: [to the machine] I know you don&#x27;t like me. The feeling is mutual. But we&#x27;re doing this anyway.</p>
<p>[The machine gurgles. Something that might be coffee drips into a carafe.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [still not looking up] You&#x27;re going to break it again.</p>
<p>Rho: [cheerful] It&#x27;s already broken. I&#x27;m just negotiating with the corpse.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna hovers near the table. Uncertain. The mine had schedules. Mealtimes. Assigned seats. She doesn&#x27;t know the rules here.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [finally glancing up] Sit. Or stand. Or leave. All acceptable.</p>
<p>[The words are permission. Avyanna sits.]</p>
<p>[Jalen returns to their datapad. Avyanna watches Rho wage war with the coffee maker.]</p>
<p>Rho: [to the machine] Yes. I know. You want the good beans. You&#x27;re getting station-grade swill. Cope.</p>
<p>[The machine makes a noise like dying hydraulics.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Eventually, Rho wins. He pours three cups of something that looks like coffee and probably contains caffeine. Maybe.]</p>
<p>[He sets one in front of Jalen. One in front of Avyanna. Keeps the third for himself.]</p>
<p>Rho: [sitting] Fair warning: it&#x27;s terrible.</p>
<p>Jalen: [taking a sip without looking] Always is.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [staring at her cup] I don&#x27;t... I&#x27;ve never had coffee.</p>
<p>Rho: [grinning] Then you don&#x27;t know what you&#x27;re missing. Which means this won&#x27;t disappoint you.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna picks up the cup. It&#x27;s warm. The smell is bitter and sharp and foreign.]</p>
<p>[She takes a cautious sip.]</p>
<p>[It tastes like burnt dirt and regret.]</p>
<p>[She swallows anyway because wasting food-wasting anything-feels like a crime.]</p>
<p>Rho: [watching her face] You hate it.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [lying] It&#x27;s fine.</p>
<p>Rho: [laughing] You&#x27;re a terrible liar. It&#x27;s okay to hate it. Half the crew hates my coffee. The other half is lying.</p>
<p>Jalen: [dryly] I don&#x27;t hate it. I&#x27;m just dead inside.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna sets the cup down carefully.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] Do you... have tea?</p>
<p>Rho: [standing immediately] Yes. Why didn&#x27;t you say so?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [confused] I thought... I thought I had to drink what you made.</p>
<p>[Rho pauses. Looks at her. Something in his expression shifts-recognition of an old wound.]</p>
<p>Rho: [carefully] You don&#x27;t. You can drink whatever you want. Or nothing. Your call.</p>
<hr>
<p>[He pulls out a different container. Tea bags in six different varieties. Sets them in front of her.]</p>
<p>Rho: Pick one. Or don&#x27;t. I&#x27;m not your supervisor.</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the options. In the mine, you got what you got. Here, she has six choices and no idea how to choose.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [without looking up] Green tea&#x27;s mild. Black tea&#x27;s strong. Herbal tea isn&#x27;t actually tea but people call it that anyway.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [pointing] Green. Please.</p>
<p>Rho: [making it] Good choice. Least likely to taste like dirt.</p>
<hr>
<p>[He makes the tea. Sets it in front of her. This time, when she sips, it&#x27;s... better. Still strange. But better.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Thank you.</p>
<p>Rho: [sitting back down] Don&#x27;t thank me. Just... drink what you like. That&#x27;s how it works here.</p>
<p>[They sit in silence. Rho drinks his terrible coffee with evident satisfaction. Jalen reads their datapad. Avyanna holds her tea and tries to understand what&#x27;s happening.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[This isn&#x27;t... anything. It&#x27;s not a meeting. Not a lesson. Not a task.]</p>
<p>[It&#x27;s just three people in a room at 0530, drinking things, existing near each other.]</p>
<p>[No one is performing. No one is proving anything.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [carefully] Do you do this every morning?</p>
<p>Rho: [nodding] Most mornings. Jalen&#x27;s always up early. I&#x27;m always up early. We collide in the galley and pretend we&#x27;re not hiding from our own thoughts.</p>
<p>Jalen: [finally looking up] I&#x27;m not hiding. I&#x27;m working.</p>
<p>Rho: [to Avyanna] They&#x27;re hiding.</p>
<p>Jalen: [returning to their datapad] This conversation is beneath me.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna almost smiles. The motion feels strange on her face.]</p>
<p>[She takes another sip of tea. It&#x27;s warmer now. Less foreign.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Can I... come back tomorrow?</p>
<p>Rho: [surprised] You don&#x27;t need permission. Galley&#x27;s open. Coffee&#x27;s terrible. Tea&#x27;s mediocre. We&#x27;ll be here.</p>
<p>Jalen: [adding] Same time. Same silence. Same existential dread.</p>
<p>Rho: [throwing a napkin at him] You&#x27;re a ray of sunshine.</p>
<p>Jalen: [catching it without looking] I know.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They fall back into silence. Comfortable. Unforced.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna drinks her tea. Rho reads something on his datapad and mutters about supply costs. Jalen&#x27;s stylus moves across their screen, plotting something that probably involves math Avyanna doesn&#x27;t understand yet.]</p>
<p>[No one demands anything. No one expects anything.]</p>
<p>[She&#x27;s just... here. And that&#x27;s allowed.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[At 0600, Jalen stands.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [to Rho] Shift change in thirty. Don&#x27;t forget the gyro calibration.</p>
<p>Rho: [saluting lazily] Aye aye, navigator.</p>
<p>[Jalen nods to Avyanna.]</p>
<p>Jalen: [to her] See you at 0530 tomorrow. Or don&#x27;t. Either way.</p>
<p>[They leave. The door hisses shut behind them.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho refills his coffee. Doesn&#x27;t offer Avyanna more tea. She&#x27;s still working on the first cup.]</p>
<p>Rho: [after a moment] In the mine, you didn&#x27;t get to choose what you drank, did you.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking her head] No. You got water. Or the stuff they called juice. It wasn&#x27;t juice.</p>
<p>Rho: [grimacing] Yeah. I&#x27;ve tasted extraction-grade &quot;juice.&quot; It&#x27;s a war crime.</p>
<p>[Rho sets down his own mug. Deliberate.]</p>
<p>Rho: Here, you get to choose. Every time. Coffee, tea, water, that terrible synthetic fruit drink Elia likes. Whatever. It&#x27;s yours to decide.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna looks at her tea.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] I don&#x27;t know how to... have preferences.</p>
<p>Rho: [leaning back] Then you practice. You try green tea. Tomorrow you try black tea. Next week you try herbal. Eventually you figure out what you like.</p>
<p>Rho: And if you never figure it out? If you just keep drinking whatever&#x27;s available? That&#x27;s fine too. Preferences aren&#x27;t mandatory. They&#x27;re just... allowed.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna absorbs this. Preferences as optional. Choice as practice, not test.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] What if I choose wrong?</p>
<p>Rho: [snorting] It&#x27;s tea, kid. Not surgery. Worst case, you don&#x27;t like it and you try something else tomorrow.</p>
<p>[He stands, rinses his cup, sets it in the cleaning rack.]</p>
<p>Rho: [turning back] The mine taught you that every choice has consequences, right? That choosing wrong means punishment?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [barely audible] Yes.</p>
<p>Rho: [nodding] Yeah. Thought so.</p>
<p>[He sits back down. Looks at her directly.]</p>
<p>Rho: Here&#x27;s the thing. Choosing the wrong tea isn&#x27;t a mistake. It&#x27;s information. &quot;I don&#x27;t like black tea&quot; is useful data. It narrows your options. Makes future choices easier.</p>
<p>Rho: The mine wanted you to be terrified of choosing. Because terrified people don&#x27;t ask for things. They just take what they&#x27;re given and call it mercy.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands tighten around her cup.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking] They said... they said we were lucky. To have rations at all.</p>
<p>Rho: [flat] They lied.</p>
<p>Rho: You weren&#x27;t lucky. You were exploited. There&#x27;s a difference.</p>
<p>[His voice drops. Not softer. Heavier.]</p>
<p>Rho: And here, you get to choose your own damn tea. Because that&#x27;s what people do. They have preferences. They express them. They change their minds. And nobody punishes them for it.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna sits with that. The tea is cooling in her hands. The galley is quiet except for the ship&#x27;s ambient hum.]</p>
<p>[She finishes the tea. Sets the cup down.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [standing] I should... I should go. Let you work.</p>
<p>Rho: [waving her off] I&#x27;m not working. I&#x27;m procrastinating. You&#x27;re fine.</p>
<p>[But he doesn&#x27;t stop her from leaving.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna reaches the door. Pauses.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [not turning around] Same time tomorrow?</p>
<p>Rho: [grinning] Same time. Same terrible coffee. Same slightly-better tea.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna leaves. The door hisses shut behind her.]</p>
<p>[In the corridor, she leans against the bulkhead and breathes.]</p>
<p>(I chose tea. I didn&#x27;t like the coffee. I said so. And nothing bad happened.)</p>
<p>[The shard at the base of her skull is warm. Quiet. Content.]</p>
<p>(The warmth at the base of her skull steadies, a wordless reassurance she translates anyway: choice, yours, safe.)</p>
<p>[She pushes off the wall and heads back to her quarters.]</p>
<p>[Tomorrow, she&#x27;ll try black tea. Just to see.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// OBSERVATION: trainee participated in crew morning ritual | DURATION: 30 minutes | SOCIAL ENGAGEMENT: appropriate | AUTONOMY EXERCISED: preference expressed without fear | ASSESSMENT: integration progressing&gt;</p>
<p>&lt;RHO PERSONAL LOG: &quot;She asked if she could come back tomorrow. Like she needed permission to exist in a space. Fucking mine. Fucking extraction economy. Tomorrow I&#x27;m making better tea.&quot;&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Scene*</p>
</div>

