:: Act1 15c Station Micro Errand Paperwork And Predators
<h1>Optional 15c: Station Micro Errand Paperwork And Predators</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 15c_station_micro_errand_paperwork_and_predators.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH15, FIRST STATION ERRAND]** &gt; *Location: Station concourse (unnamed)* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Elisira* &gt; *Teaching: &quot;helpful&quot; is not always help; politeness is wrapper; forms are teeth*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The concourse smells like hot oil, cheap perfume, and the particular tang of too many bodies pretending not to need each other.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna walks half a step behind Elisira, trying to match her pace.]</p>
<p>[Elisira moves like she belongs. Not because she&#x27;s loud. Because she&#x27;s certain.]</p>
<p>(How do you look like you belong when you&#x27;re always waiting to be corrected.)</p>
<p>Elisira: Stay close enough that you can hear me.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [automatic] Yes.</p>
<p>[Avyanna catches herself.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why.</p>
<p>[Elisira glances at her, a tiny flicker of approval.]</p>
<p>Elisira: Because this is a funnel.</p>
<p>[She gestures without moving her hands-just a small tilt of chin toward a cluster of kiosks, a queue, and a row of &quot;assistance desks&quot; with people who look too eager.]</p>
<p>Elisira: Funnels are where predators hunt.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Like the mine.</p>
<p>Elisira: Like anywhere people are scared and tired.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They&#x27;re here for a simple errand: pick up a stamped copy of a contract addendum. A paper artifact. A thing the Guild recognizes even if systems &quot;glitch.&quot;]</p>
<p>[Avyanna hates that paper matters.]</p>
<p>(Paper matters because someone can take it away. Paper matters because it can be burned.)</p>
<p>[Elisira doesn&#x27;t hate it. Elisira treats paper like a weapon with a handle.]</p>
<p>[They approach the counter.]</p>
<p>[A clerk smiles too widely.]</p>
<p>Clerk: Can I help you, miss-</p>
<p>[Her eyes flick to Avyanna&#x27;s collar tag. Too fast to be casual.]</p>
<p>Clerk: -traveler.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s skin crawls.]</p>
<p>Elisira: [pleasant] We&#x27;re here for a pickup. Code is on the slate.</p>
<p>[She slides the slate over. Not close enough for the clerk to snatch it.]</p>
<p>[The clerk&#x27;s smile tightens.]</p>
<p>Clerk: We&#x27;ll need to verify identity.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [tensing] Which-</p>
<p>Elisira: [cutting in, still pleasant] Under which jurisdiction.</p>
<p>[The clerk blinks.]</p>
<p>Clerk: Excuse me?</p>
<p>Elisira: You said &quot;need.&quot; I&#x27;m asking: need by which rule. Enforced by whom.</p>
<p>[The clerk&#x27;s eyes flick toward a security camera. Toward a uniform across the hall.]</p>
<p>[Then back.]</p>
<p>Clerk: It&#x27;s... standard.</p>
<p>Elisira: Standard is not enforceable.</p>
<p>[The clerk&#x27;s stylus taps twice against the counter.]</p>
<p>Clerk: Fine. Sign here.</p>
<p>[She prints a slip with a pen attached by chain.]</p>
<p>[The slip is a trap with polite edges: it asks for name, origin, and &quot;additional contacts.&quot;]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>(Additional contacts means: who can we threaten.)</p>
<p>Elisira: [to Avyanna, quiet] You don&#x27;t sign anything you didn&#x27;t request.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [whisper] I didn&#x27;t request this.</p>
<p>Elisira: Correct.</p>
<p>[Elisira takes the pen-not from the clerk&#x27;s hand, from the counter.]</p>
<p>Elisira: [pleasant] We&#x27;re declining voluntary disclosure.</p>
<p>Clerk: It&#x27;s required.</p>
<p>Elisira: Then cite it.</p>
<p>[Silence.]</p>
<p>[The clerk&#x27;s smile becomes brittle.]</p>
<p>Clerk: If you don&#x27;t cooperate, the pickup may be delayed.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s heart rate spikes.]</p>
<p>(Delay means loss. Loss means punishment. Loss means hunger.)</p>
<p>Elisira: Then delay it.</p>
<p>[She says it like: we have all day. Like time can&#x27;t be weaponized here.]</p>
<p>Elisira: We&#x27;ll file a complaint with the arbitration desk. We&#x27;ll note the attempted coercion. We&#x27;ll request the security footage.</p>
<p>[The clerk&#x27;s eyes widen, just a fraction.]</p>
<p>[She reaches under the counter and produces the stamped packet like it&#x27;s always been there.]</p>
<p>Clerk: No need to escalate.</p>
<p>Elisira: Good.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They step away.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s knees feel like they&#x27;re trying to unlock.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [breathing] You can just... do that.</p>
<p>Elisira: Yes.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why didn&#x27;t she-</p>
<p>Elisira: Because the clerk wasn&#x27;t enforcing policy. She was testing a boundary.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Like a-</p>
<p>Elisira: Predator.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands tremble as she clutches the packet.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: What if she had called security.</p>
<p>Elisira: Then we&#x27;d have receipts.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That sounds like Vesper.</p>
<p>Elisira: Vesper taught me half of it. I taught her the other half. It&#x27;s incestuous.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [a startled laugh] That&#x27;s not-</p>
<p>Elisira: [deadpan] It&#x27;s a metaphor. Do not repeat it.</p>
<hr>
<p>[A man steps into their path.]</p>
<p>[Not uniformed. Not armed. Just... friendly.]</p>
<p>Man: Hey. You look lost. I know where the arbitration wing is. I can-</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s mouth opens.]</p>
<p>[The mine reflex tries to offer politeness as payment.]</p>
<p>Elisira: No thank you.</p>
<p>Man: I&#x27;m just helping.</p>
<p>Elisira: We did not request help.</p>
<p>Man: Wow. Hostile.</p>
<p>Elisira: [pleasant] Correct.</p>
<p>[They walk around him.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s chest tightens as if waiting for the hit that follows refusal.]</p>
<p>[None comes.]</p>
<p>[The man mutters something under his breath and moves on, scanning for softer prey.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] No thank you.</p>
<p>Elisira: Yes.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s... allowed.</p>
<p>Elisira: It&#x27;s required.</p>
<p>[Avyanna looks at her.]</p>
<p>Elisira: For survival.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Back at the docking tunnel, Avyanna exhales like she&#x27;s been holding her breath since they left the ship.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I kept thinking... if I&#x27;m rude, something bad happens.</p>
<p>Elisira: That&#x27;s because something bad used to happen.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Does it ever stop feeling like-</p>
<p>Elisira: [cutting in, softer than usual] Yes.</p>
<p>[A pause.]</p>
<p>Elisira: Not fast. But yes.</p>
<p>[Avyanna nods.]</p>
<p>[She presses the stamped packet to her chest like it can keep her safe.]</p>
<p>(Paper is teeth. But sometimes it bites the right thing.)</p>
<hr>
<p>[They don&#x27;t go straight back.]</p>
<p>[Elisira takes the long route through the concourse on purpose.]</p>
<p>[Not because she likes crowds. Because she likes information.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why are we-</p>
<p>Elisira: Watching.</p>
<p>[They pause near a wall of public postings.]</p>
<p>[Not a bulletin board. A contract board. Smaller than the Guild&#x27;s, but the same bones: jobs, fees, penalties, a thousand ways to make desperation look like choice.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna reads a posting aloud without thinking.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: &quot;Processing surcharge applies to late submissions.&quot;</p>
<p>[Her stomach twists.]</p>
<p>(Processing surcharge. Mine word. Station word. Same shape.)</p>
<p>Elisira: What does that mean.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [automatic] It means... pay.</p>
<p>Elisira: That&#x27;s the effect. Not the meaning.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [working] It means they&#x27;re charging for time they didn&#x27;t lose. They&#x27;re charging for... being behind.</p>
<p>Elisira: Who benefits.</p>
<p>Avyanna: The office. The broker. Whoever owns the desk.</p>
<p>Elisira: Who enforces it.</p>
<p>Avyanna: The clerk. The system. The fact that if you miss a submission, you lose your claim.</p>
<p>Elisira: Good.</p>
<hr>
<p>[A woman approaches them.]</p>
<p>[Mid-thirties, expensive coat, smile tuned for crowds. She carries a badge that looks real enough to be dangerous.]</p>
<p>Woman: You look like you&#x27;re having trouble with the boards.</p>
<p>Elisira: No.</p>
<p>Woman: I can help you file. I know the system. I can get you processed faster.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s mouth goes dry.]</p>
<p>(Faster means: I own you now.)</p>
<p>[The woman&#x27;s gaze flicks to Avyanna again. Too curious.]</p>
<p>Woman: You&#x27;re new. You don&#x27;t want to get tripped up by bureaucracy. It&#x27;s such a shame when people lose claims over small mistakes.</p>
<p>[She smiles wider, as if pity is a gift.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna feels her body prepare the mine-script: apologize, agree, accept the hook.]</p>
<p>[Elisira doesn&#x27;t raise her voice.]</p>
<p>Elisira: No thank you.</p>
<p>Woman: I&#x27;m not charging.</p>
<p>Elisira: Then you are lying.</p>
<p>[The woman&#x27;s smile tightens.]</p>
<p>Woman: Excuse me?</p>
<p>Elisira: People who do labor for free in systems like this are buying something else.</p>
<p>Woman: I&#x27;m just-</p>
<p>Elisira: Helping.</p>
<p>Elisira: We did not request help.</p>
<p>[The woman&#x27;s eyes harden, just for a blink. A tell.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet, to Elisira] Anger at refusal.</p>
<p>[Elisira&#x27;s gaze flicks to her. Approval without softness.]</p>
<p>Elisira: Correct.</p>
<p>[The woman recovers her smile.]</p>
<p>Woman: You don&#x27;t have to be rude.</p>
<p>Elisira: I do.</p>
<p>Woman: That&#x27;s going to make you enemies.</p>
<p>Elisira: It&#x27;s a public concourse. Everyone is already an enemy. The difference is which ones pretend.</p>
<p>[The woman&#x27;s smile drops entirely.]</p>
<p>Woman: Fine. Good luck.</p>
<p>[She walks away quickly, scanning for someone who will trade fear for assistance.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [breathing] I almost-</p>
<p>Elisira: Took the hook.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Yes.</p>
<p>Elisira: That&#x27;s normal.</p>
<p>Avyanna: It doesn&#x27;t feel normal.</p>
<p>Elisira: It feels like training data.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Am I... always going to be that easy.</p>
<p>Elisira: No.</p>
<p>Elisira: You just proved it.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They walk back toward the docking tunnel.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna clutches the stamped packet less like a lifeline and more like evidence.]</p>
<p>(Politeness is wrapper. Evaluate the ask.)</p>
<p>[She repeats it silently until the words stop feeling like a borrowed tool and start feeling like hers.]</p>
</div>

