:: Act1 16 Breach Hymn
<h1>Chapter 16: Breach Hymn</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 16_breach_hymn.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **LUMEN THIEF - DEMOLITIONS TRAINING MANUAL (RESTRICTED):** &gt; *Subject: Controlled Destruction* &gt; *Instructor: Rho Sable* &gt; *Trainee: Avyanna Lagrange* &gt; *Summary: Making things fall is easy. Making them fall where you want is the job.* &gt; *Rule 1: Know what&#x27;s on the other side of the wall.* &gt; *Rule 2: Precision is slower. Precision is the point.* &gt; *Rule 3: The shortcut always costs more than it saves.* &gt; *Addendum: If you&#x27;re in a hurry, you&#x27;re already losing.*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The range is in the cargo hold&#x27;s lower section-a reinforced bay that smells like ozone and old polymer and something sharp that catches in the back of Avyanna&#x27;s throat. The walls are analog-hardened against corridor drift; someone has scratched &quot;NO LATTICE INTERFERENCE&quot; into the blast door frame.]</p>
<p>[Rho is already there when she arrives. He&#x27;s setting up a simulation grid: holographic walls projected onto a metal frame, sensors embedded in the deck to track debris patterns.]</p>
<p>[He doesn&#x27;t look up.]</p>
<p>Rho: You&#x27;re early.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Elisira&#x27;s lesson ran short.</p>
<p>Rho: Elisira&#x27;s lessons never run short. She let you think it did.</p>
<p>[Avyanna blinks. He&#x27;s right, probably. Everything Elisira does is deliberate.]</p>
<p>[Rho finishes calibrating the grid. The holographic walls flicker-gray and solid-looking, like real bulkheads. He steps back, wipes his hands on his thighs, and finally meets her eyes.]</p>
<p>Rho: Ready to learn how to break things?</p>
<p>Avyanna: I&#x27;ve broken things before.</p>
<p>Rho: Yeah. That&#x27;s not the same.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The range setup is simple: three simulated walls, each with different structural compositions displayed on a floating readout. Behind each wall, a cluster of red dots-simulated personnel. Hostiles. Civilians. Unknowns.]</p>
<p>[Rho hands her a pair of safety lenses. They&#x27;re scratched and heavy.]</p>
<p>Rho: The goal isn&#x27;t destruction. The goal is *access*. You want through a wall, not through whatever&#x27;s behind it.</p>
<p>[Avyanna puts on the lenses. The world tints amber.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: What if what&#x27;s behind it is hostile?</p>
<p>Rho: Then you figure that out *before* you blow the wall. Not after.</p>
<p>[He taps a control. The first simulated wall highlights-standard station composite, internal bracing visible in the overlay.]</p>
<p>Rho: First lesson: reading structure. Every wall tells you how it wants to fall.</p>
<hr>
<p>[He walks her through the basics.]</p>
<p>[Stress points. Load-bearing vs cosmetic. The difference between &quot;opens cleanly&quot; and &quot;collapses in a cascade that kills everyone in the next three rooms.&quot;]</p>
<p>[Avyanna listens. Her hands itch for something to hold-a wrench, a tool, anything that makes her feel less like a student and more like someone who belongs here.]</p>
<p>[Rho talks with his hands. Big gestures, precise despite their size. She notices the scars on his knuckles-different from Elisira&#x27;s. These are burns, not cuts. Chemical or thermal, healed rough.]</p>
<p>Rho: See that brace? If you hit it wrong, the whole section torques. Clean breach becomes a hull compromise.</p>
<p>Avyanna: And if it&#x27;s an emergency? If there&#x27;s no time to read the structure?</p>
<p>[Rho&#x27;s jaw tightens. Just for a second. The grin flickers-not armor snapping into place, but armor *slipping*. He catches it. Resets it. Too slow for casual.]</p>
<p>Rho: Then you&#x27;re already in trouble. And trouble means people die.</p>
<hr>
<p>[He sets up the first exercise: a simulated door, reinforced, with a lock mechanism and a timer.]</p>
<p>Rho: Standard Guild security door. You&#x27;ve got thirty seconds to get through it without triggering the alarm on the other side.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Thirty seconds isn&#x27;t-</p>
<p>Rho: Yeah. It isn&#x27;t. That&#x27;s the point.</p>
<p>[He hands her a kit-small charges, placement tools, a detonator with a physical switch. No smart interface. Dumb reliability. A manifest tag on the case reads &quot;ALLOCATION: TRAINING-VESPER APPROVED (GRUDGINGLY).&quot;]</p>
<p>Rho: Go.</p>
<p>[Avyanna moves. Her hands are steadier than she expected. The mine taught her to work fast, to work small, to occupy as little space and attention as possible.]</p>
<p>[She finds the hinges. Places the first charge. Too high-she adjusts. The second charge goes on the lock mechanism. The timer ticks.]</p>
<p>[She triggers the detonator.]</p>
<p>[The door simulation fractures-but wrong. The debris pattern sprays backward, toward her position. Red warning lights flash across the safety lenses.]</p>
<p>Rho: Dead.</p>
<p>Avyanna: What?</p>
<p>Rho: You shaped the charge to push inward. But you didn&#x27;t account for the lock&#x27;s reinforcement. It redirected the blast.</p>
<p>[He taps the control. The simulation resets.]</p>
<p>Rho: Try again.</p>
<hr>
<p>[She tries again.]</p>
<p>[And again.]</p>
<p>[The fourth attempt, the door opens cleanly. No debris spray. No alarm trigger. The red dots behind the door remain stationary-undisturbed.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands are shaking slightly. Not fear. Adrenaline. The shard hums at the base of her skull-warm, attentive.]</p>
<p>Rho: Better.</p>
<p>Avyanna: It took four tries.</p>
<p>Rho: First time I did this drill, it took me eleven.</p>
<p>[She stares at him.]</p>
<p>Rho: [shrugging] What? I&#x27;m not naturally talented. I just practice until I stop being terrible.</p>
<p>[The honesty is disarming. Avyanna doesn&#x27;t know what to do with it.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[They move to the second exercise: a wall with civilians on the other side.]</p>
<p>[The simulation shows them as blue dots-clustered, unaware, positioned where a careless breach would kill them.]</p>
<p>Rho: Same wall. Different problem. How do you get through without casualties?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [studying the layout] Move them first?</p>
<p>Rho: Can&#x27;t. They don&#x27;t know you&#x27;re coming. Moving them tips off the hostiles in the next section.</p>
<p>[Avyanna frowns. The geometry is wrong. Every angle she can see puts the breach zone too close to the civilians.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Then you don&#x27;t go through this wall.</p>
<p>[Rho&#x27;s eyebrows lift. Interest, not approval-not yet.]</p>
<p>Rho: Go on.</p>
<p>Avyanna: You find a different entry point. One that doesn&#x27;t put them at risk.</p>
<p>Rho: What if this is the only entry point?</p>
<p>Avyanna: Then you wait. Or you change the mission parameters. Or you-</p>
<p>[She stops. The heat at the base of her skull pulses-frustration, maybe. The shard doesn&#x27;t like constraints it can&#x27;t solve.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I don&#x27;t know.</p>
<p>Rho: That&#x27;s the right answer.</p>
<p>[He taps the control. The simulation zooms out, showing the full layout-multiple entry vectors, timing windows, patrol patterns.]</p>
<p>Rho: There&#x27;s always another way. The shortcut is the lie that says there isn&#x27;t.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They take a break. Rho produces a thermos from somewhere-coffee, or the ship&#x27;s approximation of it. He pours two cups.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna takes hers. The warmth is grounding. The shard settles from frustrated to merely present.]</p>
<p>Rho: You&#x27;re doing better than I expected.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [wary] Is that a compliment?</p>
<p>Rho: It&#x27;s an observation. Compliments are Vesper&#x27;s department.</p>
<p>[He drinks. The silence stretches. Comfortable, almost. The range hums with residual charge.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why do you do this?</p>
<p>Rho: Teach?</p>
<p>Avyanna: Demolitions. Breaking things. Making them fall.</p>
<p>[Rho&#x27;s cup pauses halfway to his mouth. The grin doesn&#x27;t fade, but something behind it shifts-like a door closing, then forcing itself open again.]</p>
<p>Rho: Because I&#x27;m good at it. And because someone has to be.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s not an answer.</p>
<p>Rho: It&#x27;s the one I&#x27;ve got.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The next exercise is harder.]</p>
<p>[Rho sets up a scenario: a hull breach in progress, structural integrity failing, hostiles on one side and crew on the other. The timer starts at sixty seconds.]</p>
<p>Rho: You can seal the breach with a shaped charge-collapse the corridor, buy time for evacuation. But the collapse will kill the hostiles.</p>
<p>Avyanna: They&#x27;re hostiles. They&#x27;re trying to-</p>
<p>Rho: They&#x27;re people. Maybe hired. Maybe coerced. Maybe desperate. Doesn&#x27;t matter. They&#x27;re still people.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: So what&#x27;s the other option?</p>
<p>Rho: Slower. More precise. You shape the charge differently-collapse only the section you need, leave an exit route for them. Evacuation takes longer. More risk to the crew.</p>
<p>[He watches her. No guidance. No hints.]</p>
<p>Rho: Choose.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the simulation. The timer ticks. Fifty-three seconds. Fifty-two.]</p>
<p>[The shard pulses-not heat, not cold. Something else. Pressure. Like it&#x27;s waiting to see what she&#x27;ll do.]</p>
<p>[She thinks of the mine. Of supervisors who made choices like this every day. &quot;Acceptable losses.&quot; &quot;Necessary sacrifices.&quot; Words that meant: *someone else pays so I don&#x27;t have to.*]</p>
<p>(In the Kennel, I was the acceptable loss. I was the necessary sacrifice. I will not be the one who decides someone else is.)</p>
<p>Avyanna: The slower way.</p>
<p>Rho: Even with the risk?</p>
<p>Avyanna: Even with the risk.</p>
<p>[Rho nods. His face is unreadable.]</p>
<p>Rho: Do it.</p>
<hr>
<p>[She fails the first attempt. The collapse is too wide-one of the blue dots winks out. Civilian casualty.]</p>
<p>[She fails the second attempt. The breach isn&#x27;t sealed in time. The timer hits zero.]</p>
<p>[The third attempt, she gets it right. The hostiles escape through their exit route. The crew evacuates. The breach holds.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands are shaking again. Not adrenaline this time. Something else.]</p>
<p>Rho: Slower is harder. Slower takes practice. But slower is what we do.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why?</p>
<p>[The question comes out sharper than she intended. The shard&#x27;s pressure hasn&#x27;t faded-it&#x27;s watching, listening, *waiting.*]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why does it matter? If they&#x27;re hostile-if they&#x27;re trying to kill us-why does it matter if they have an exit?</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho is quiet for a long moment. The range hums. Somewhere in the ship, a ventilation system cycles.]</p>
<p>[When he speaks, the humor is gone. His voice is flat, careful, like he&#x27;s reciting something he&#x27;s said before-to himself, in the dark, when no one else was listening.]</p>
<p>Rho: Because shortcuts have a cost. And the cost is never the one you expect.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s not-</p>
<p>Rho: I killed thirty-seven people with a shortcut.</p>
<p>[The words land like a physical weight. Avyanna&#x27;s mouth closes.]</p>
<p>[Rho doesn&#x27;t look at her. He&#x27;s looking at the simulation grid-at the blue dots, the red dots, the debris patterns that mark where walls used to be.]</p>
<p>Rho: I was Compact military. Then rim. Then mercenary. Whatever paid, wherever the work was. I was good at it. Fast. Efficient.</p>
<p>[His hands curl around the thermos. The metal creaks.]</p>
<p>Rho: There was a situation. Andros Station. Under siege. Hostages in one section, hostiles in another. Command said we had a window-forty seconds to breach, extract, and evac before the station&#x27;s core went critical.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] What happened?</p>
<p>Rho: I took the shortcut. Shaped charge through the main corridor. Fast. Clean. The hostiles went down. The window held.</p>
<p>[A beat.]</p>
<p>Rho: Except the corridor connected to a secondary habitation module. Civilians. Families. The shockwave killed them before they knew we were there.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s chest tightens. The shard goes cold-not pain, but something like recognition. Like it knows this shape of grief.]</p>
<p>Rho: Thirty-seven people. Twelve of them were children.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The silence stretches. The range&#x27;s ambient hum fills the space between them.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna doesn&#x27;t know what to say. In the mine, people died all the time. You learned not to look. Not to count. Not to carry the weight of faces you couldn&#x27;t save.]</p>
<p>[But Rho carries them. She can see it now-in the set of his shoulders, the tightness around his eyes, the way his jokes deflect before anyone can ask.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: The crew knows?</p>
<p>Rho: Elia knows. Elisira figured it out. Vesper has access to records she shouldn&#x27;t. Jalen... Jalen lost people too. Different way. Same weight.</p>
<p>Avyanna: And they still-</p>
<p>Rho: They still trust me.</p>
<p>[He says it like he doesn&#x27;t understand it. Like every day he wakes up expecting them to finally realize what he is.]</p>
<p>Rho: Elia gave me a rule. *Precision is the only absolution.* She didn&#x27;t forgive me. She just... kept trusting me anyway. Made me earn it.</p>
<p>[He looks at Avyanna. Really looks-not the casual assessment of a teacher, but something rawer. Someone deciding how much of themselves to show.]</p>
<p>Rho: That&#x27;s why we choose the slower way. That&#x27;s why shortcuts cost more than they save. Because the people behind those walls-the blue dots, the red dots, whoever they are-they&#x27;re not numbers. They&#x27;re faces you&#x27;ll carry forever.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat is tight. The heat at the base of her skull has shifted-not cold anymore, but not warm either. Present. Witnessing.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I&#x27;m sorry.</p>
<p>Rho: [shaking his head] Don&#x27;t be. Just... remember.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Remember what?</p>
<p>Rho: That the shortcut always lies. It says it&#x27;s faster. It says it&#x27;s cleaner. It says the cost is acceptable.</p>
<p>[He sets down the thermos. His hands are steady again-the mask reassembling, the armor clicking back into place.]</p>
<p>Rho: The cost is never acceptable. It&#x27;s just the one you haven&#x27;t paid yet.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They run through two more exercises. Avyanna&#x27;s focus is sharper now-not just technical, but moral. She reads the simulations differently. The blue dots aren&#x27;t abstractions anymore. They&#x27;re faces she hasn&#x27;t met yet.]</p>
<p>[Rho&#x27;s teaching shifts too. Less joking. More direct. He points out her mistakes without softening them, but he also names what she&#x27;s doing right.]</p>
<p>Rho: Good. You&#x27;re thinking about the exit before you think about the entry.</p>
<p>Avyanna: You said there&#x27;s always another way.</p>
<p>Rho: There is. The trick is being patient enough to find it.</p>
<hr>
<p>[At the end of the session, Rho packs up the simulation grid. The cargo hold returns to its default state-crates, cargo nets, the quiet hum of environmental systems.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna helps without being asked. The work is familiar-lifting, stacking, fitting pieces into spaces where they belong. The mine taught her this much.]</p>
<p>Rho: Same time tomorrow?</p>
<p>Avyanna: If you want.</p>
<p>Rho: I want.</p>
<p>[He pauses, one hand on a crate.]</p>
<p>Rho: Avyanna.</p>
<p>[She looks up.]</p>
<p>Rho: You asked why I do this. Breaking things. Making them fall.</p>
<p>[His voice is lighter now-the armor back, the jokes hovering at the edge. But underneath, something true.]</p>
<p>Rho: I do it because I already know what happens when you do it wrong. And I&#x27;d rather teach someone to do it right than watch them learn the way I did.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Later, in the corridor outside the cargo hold, Avyanna pauses.]</p>
<p>[The shard hums-low, steady. Not pain. Not pressure. Just... presence. Acknowledgment.]</p>
<p>(He carries thirty-seven faces.)</p>
<p>[The thought settles into her like a new weight. Not crushing. Just there.]</p>
<p>(I carry the Kennel. He carries the corridor. Jalen carries Kettering&#x27;s Rest. Everyone on this ship carries something.)</p>
<p>[She thinks of Elia&#x27;s rule: *Precision is the only absolution.*]</p>
<p>[It doesn&#x27;t sound like forgiveness. It sounds like a job. Something you do every day, whether you feel like it or not. A discipline instead of a pardon.]</p>
<p>(Maybe that&#x27;s what floors are. Not absolution. Just... the work that makes you worth trusting.)</p>
<p>[The heat along her spine spreads-warmer now. Agreement, maybe. Or just the shard learning alongside her.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna walks back toward her bunk. The ship hums. Somewhere ahead, someone is arguing about the coffee machine again.]</p>
<p>[She almost smiles.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// OBSERVATION: trainee completed demolitions drill | INFERENCE: moral framework strengthening | CONFIDENCE: 0.81 | NOTE: slower is harder. slower is what we do.&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>## Coda - Rho&#x27;s Ledger</p>
<p>[0300. The cargo hold is empty. The simulation grid is packed away. The deck plates are cold under Rho&#x27;s boots.]</p>
<p>[He sits on a crate in the dark, datapad in hand. The screen&#x27;s glow is the only light-blue and clinical, washing out the color in his face.]</p>
<p>[The file is encrypted. Three layers. Cinnamon could break it-she&#x27;s broken harder-but she won&#x27;t. Trust boundary. Some doors stay closed because someone asks, not because they&#x27;re locked.]</p>
<p>**LEDGER - PERSONAL - RHO SABLE**</p>
<p>[The entries are names.]</p>
<p>[Thirty-seven of them at the top. Andros Station. The corridor. The shortcut that wasn&#x27;t.]</p>
<p>[Below that: others. People who died because he was fast instead of careful. People who died because he followed orders. People who died because he was young and stupid and believed that &quot;acceptable losses&quot; was a real thing.]</p>
<p>[He doesn&#x27;t read the names. He knows them. They&#x27;re carved into the back of his skull, behind his eyes, in the place where dreams should be.]</p>
<p>[Tonight, he adds a new entry. Not a name. A number.]</p>
<p>**Days since last shortcut: 847**</p>
<p>[He stares at it. The number feels fragile. Tomorrow it will be 848. Then 849. Then a thousand, maybe. Or zero, if he screws up.]</p>
<p>[The jokes are armor. Everyone knows that. Rho knows they know. It doesn&#x27;t matter. The armor works because it gives people something to react to-something easier than the truth.]</p>
<p>[The truth is this: the ledger is discipline. The count is work. Every day he doesn&#x27;t take the shortcut is a floor under someone else&#x27;s feet.]</p>
<p>*Precision is the only absolution.*</p>
<p>[He&#x27;d laughed when she said it. A short, bitter sound. &quot;I&#x27;m not looking for absolution,&quot; he&#x27;d told her.]</p>
<p>[And Elia-small and calm and carrying her own weight of faces-had just looked at him.]</p>
<p>*&quot;Then what are you looking for?&quot;*</p>
<p>[He still doesn&#x27;t have an answer. But he has the ledger. He has the count. He has tomorrow, and the day after, and every day after that where he doesn&#x27;t take the shortcut.]</p>
<p>[That&#x27;s not absolution. That&#x27;s not forgiveness. That&#x27;s just... staying alive long enough to do the work.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho closes the datapad. The cargo hold goes dark.]</p>
<p>[Somewhere in the ship, someone laughs. Jalen, probably-or Nyx, if they&#x27;re feeling bold. The sound is muffled, distant, real.]</p>
<p>[He sits with it for a moment. The laughter. The hum of the ship. The weight of the faces he carries.]</p>
<p>[Then he stands. Rolls his shoulders. Lets the grin slide back into place like a familiar mask.]</p>
<p>[Tomorrow, he teaches Avyanna how to make a wall fall without hurting anyone behind it. Tomorrow, the count goes to 848.]</p>
<p>[Tonight, he adds the new number to the ledger and doesn&#x27;t sleep.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[The next morning, Avyanna finds Rho in the galley with Cinnamon&#x27;s interface open on a datapad.]</p>
<p>[Numbers scroll across the screen-percentages, curves, compound functions that make her head hurt.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [cautious] What&#x27;s that.</p>
<p>Rho: [not looking up] Math.</p>
<p>Avyanna: I know that. What kind.</p>
<p>Rho: The kind that keeps people enslaved.</p>
<p>[He taps the screen. A debt contract fills the display-dense legalese wrapped around a single interest rate.]</p>
<p>Rho: You know what this number means?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [reading] Twenty-two percent annual interest.</p>
<p>Rho: No.</p>
<p>[He looks at her. The mask-grin is gone.]</p>
<p>Rho: It means they never intended you to pay it off.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s stomach drops.]</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// DEMONSTRATION AVAILABLE: compound interest visualization | RECOMMEND: show her the curve&gt;</p>
<p>[The screen shifts. A graph appears-a line that starts flat, then curves upward like a scream.]</p>
<p>Rho: This is what twenty-two percent does over time. Every year, you owe more. Every payment you make barely touches the principal.</p>
<p>Avyanna: But if I just work harder-</p>
<p>Rho: No.</p>
<p>[He says it flat. Final.]</p>
<p>Rho: You can&#x27;t outwork compound interest. That&#x27;s the point. They built the math to be unbeatable.</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// CALCULATION: at 22% annual interest, original debt of 50k credits | TIME TO DOUBLE: 3.5 years | TIME TO QUADRUPLE: 7 years | ASSUMING MINIMUM PAYMENTS: never resolves&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna reads the numbers. Her hands go cold.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] I would have died there.</p>
<p>Rho: Yes.</p>
<p>Rho: Or your kids would&#x27;ve. Or their kids. That&#x27;s the design.</p>
<p>[He swipes to a different screen-a cleaner contract, different numbers.]</p>
<p>Rho: This is what non-predatory lending looks like. Five percent. Fixed term. No compound interest on missed payments.</p>
<p>Rho: The math doesn&#x27;t trap you. It just... exists.</p>
<p>Avyanna: The mine didn&#x27;t teach us about interest rates.</p>
<p>Rho: Of course they didn&#x27;t. If you understood the math, you&#x27;d understand you were being robbed.</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// PHILOSOPHY: innumeracy is a control tool | OBSERVATION: people who can&#x27;t calculate percentages can&#x27;t argue with debt claims | STRATEGY: teach the math, break the control&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the graphs.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: So if someone won&#x27;t show me the math...</p>
<p>Rho: They&#x27;re lying.</p>
<p>Rho: Or they&#x27;re too embarrassed to admit they don&#x27;t understand it either.</p>
<p>[He pulls up another screen-shaped charge calculations, blast radius formulas, safety margins.]</p>
<p>Rho: This is how I plan breaches. Math. Precision. I can&#x27;t afford to guess.</p>
<p>Rho: If I get the angle wrong by five degrees, the blast goes through the wall and kills someone behind it.</p>
<p>Rho: If I get the compound wrong by ten percent, the charge doesn&#x27;t breach at all and we&#x27;re trapped.</p>
<p>[He looks at her.]</p>
<p>Rho: Numbers don&#x27;t lie. They don&#x27;t care about your story. They just... are.</p>
<p>Rho: That&#x27;s why they&#x27;re powerful. And that&#x27;s why people who want to control you make sure you never learn them.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slow, tasting it] So learning math is...</p>
<p>Rho: Leverage.</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// LESSON PLAN AVAILABLE: basic percentages, compound interest, probability, statistical literacy | ESTIMATED TIME: 6 hours distributed | OUTCOME: quantitative ammunition against exploitation&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: Cinnamon wants to teach me.</p>
<p>Rho: Good. Let her.</p>
<p>Rho: Percentages first. Then compound interest. Then probability-so you know when someone&#x27;s selling you a bad bet.</p>
<p>Avyanna: And then I can...</p>
<p>Rho: Argue. Prove. Calculate your own risk instead of trusting theirs.</p>
<p>[He closes the datapad.]</p>
<p>Rho: They kept you innumerate for a reason. We&#x27;re fixing that.</p>
<p>[Avyanna feels something shift. Like a lock she didn&#x27;t know existed just... opened.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Thank you.</p>
<p>Rho: [grin sliding back] Don&#x27;t thank me yet. Cinnamon&#x27;s a brutal teacher. She&#x27;ll make you show your work.</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// AFFIRMATIVE: precision is required | NO SHORTCUTS | UNDERSTANDING &gt; MEMORIZATION&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna almost laughs. Almost.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I think I can handle that.</p>
<p>Rho: Good.</p>
<p>[He stands, stretches, lets the dad-joke energy return like a comfortable coat.]</p>
<p>Rho: Now go eat breakfast. Can&#x27;t learn math on an empty stomach. That&#x27;s just bad engineering.</p>
<p>[Avyanna watches him go. The datapad stays on the table, numbers still scrolling.]</p>
<p>[She picks it up. Reads the compound interest curve again.]</p>
<p>[This time, she understands what she&#x27;s looking at.]</p>
<p>[This time, the numbers are hers.]</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Chapter 16*</p>
</div>

