:: Act1 17b Complaint Posting
<h1>Optional 17b: Complaint Posting</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 17b_complaint_posting.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH17, SHIP LIFE WEEK TWO]** &gt; *Location: Lumen Thief common room* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Rho, Elia, Bubbles* &gt; *Teaching: Sparkle Doctrine basics, complaint as communication, conflict without punishment*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The common room is the ship&#x27;s informal heart. Mismatched furniture. A wall-mounted screen showing station news. A shelf of books, games, and data chips. And-prominently displayed-a digital board labeled &quot;COMPLAINTS AND OBSERVATIONS.&quot;]</p>
<p>[Avyanna sits on the couch with a cup of tea, watching Rho and Elia argue about something involving the climate control system.]</p>
<p>Rho: [exasperated] I&#x27;m just saying, if you&#x27;re cold, wear a jacket. The rest of us are fine.</p>
<p>Elia: [flat] I&#x27;m not cold. The cargo bay is cold. There&#x27;s ice forming on the bulkhead seals.</p>
<p>Rho: [defensive] That&#x27;s... that&#x27;s probably fine.</p>
<p>Elia: [staring at him] Ice. On the seals.</p>
<p>Rho: [sighing] Fine. I&#x27;ll check the heating circuits. Again.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Elia pulls out a datapad. Taps something. A notification chimes on the wall-mounted board.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna watches as new text appears on the board:]</p>
<p>**COMPLAINT #847: Cargo bay heating insufficient. Ice formation observed on bulkhead seals. Safety concern. Requesting repair priority escalation. -Elia**</p>
<p>Rho: [groaning] You&#x27;re posting it?</p>
<p>Elia: [matter-of-fact] Yes. So it&#x27;s documented. So you can&#x27;t forget. So if the seals fail, we have a record that I warned you.</p>
<p>Rho: [muttering] I&#x27;m not going to forget.</p>
<p>Elia: [dry] You forgot last month.</p>
<p>Rho: [pointing at her] That was different.</p>
<p>Elia: [raising an eyebrow] How.</p>
<p>Rho: [pause] ...I don&#x27;t have a good answer for that.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Bubbles hovers nearby, lights pulsing with what might be amusement.]</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: complaint posted per protocol | COMPLAINT VALID | RECOMMENDATION: repair within 48 hours to prevent seal degradation | ALSO: rho has history of forgetting maintenance tasks | RECEIPTS AVAILABLE&gt;</p>
<p>Rho: [to Bubbles] You&#x27;re supposed to be on my side.</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// CORRECTION: i am on the side of operational safety and accurate record-keeping | YOUR SIDE IS NOT A CATEGORY&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna almost smiles. Watching Rho get roasted by a drone is strangely comforting.]</p>
<hr>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] What is... that?</p>
<p>[She nods at the complaints board.]</p>
<p>Rho: [sitting heavily on the couch] That is the bane of my existence.</p>
<p>Elia: [sitting across from him] That is Sparkle Doctrine in action.</p>
<p>[Avyanna looks between them. Confused.]</p>
<p>Elia: [to Avyanna] You don&#x27;t know Sparkle Doctrine yet?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking her head] No.</p>
<p>Rho: [grinning despite himself] Oh, you&#x27;re in for a treat. Elia, explain. You&#x27;re better at the theory.</p>
<p>Elia: [considering] Sparkle Doctrine is a conflict resolution framework. Instead of letting grievances fester or escalate to violence, you post them publicly. Complaint, observation, concern-whatever it is, you document it. Publicly. With receipts.</p>
<hr>
<p>Avyanna: [frowning] Why publicly?</p>
<p>Elia: [precise] Because private complaints can be ignored, dismissed, or retaliated against without witnesses. Public complaints have accountability built in.</p>
<p>Elia: [gesturing at the board] Everyone on this ship can see that I posted a complaint about the cargo bay heating. Rho can&#x27;t pretend I didn&#x27;t warn him. If he ignores it and the seals fail, the record shows negligence. If he fixes it, the record shows responsiveness.</p>
<p>Rho: [adding] And if I fix it, I get to post a response saying &quot;complaint resolved, heating repaired.&quot; Then I look competent.</p>
<p>Elia: [dry] Theoretical competence.</p>
<p>Rho: [wounded] I&#x27;m very competent.</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// ADDENDUM: sparkle doctrine prevents gaslighting | PUBLIC RECORD MEANS DISPUTES CANNOT BE MEMORY-BASED | &quot;I TOLD YOU&quot; VS &quot;NO YOU DIDN&#x27;T&quot; BECOMES OBSOLETE | RECEIPTS EXIST&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slow] So... it&#x27;s about documentation. Again.</p>
<p>Elia: [nodding] Everything here is about documentation. Consent, contracts, complaints. If it&#x27;s not documented, it&#x27;s not real.</p>
<p>Rho: [leaning forward] But here&#x27;s the thing. Sparkle isn&#x27;t just about complaints. It&#x27;s also about observations. Compliments. Random thoughts. Anything you want the crew to know.</p>
<p>[He pulls up the board on his datapad, scrolls.]</p>
<p>Rho: [reading] &quot;Observation #723: Rho&#x27;s coffee is getting worse. Possible correlation with cheap station beans. Requesting upgrade budget. -Jalen.&quot;</p>
<p>[He grins.]</p>
<p>Rho: [to Avyanna] See? Not a complaint. Just an observation. But now it&#x27;s on record. And now Vesper knows that if crew morale tanks, it might be coffee-related.</p>
<hr>
<p>Elia: [pulling up another entry] &quot;Complaint #699: Common room couch has a spring that attacks the lower back. Requesting replacement or repair. -Nyx.&quot;</p>
<p>[She pats the couch they&#x27;re sitting on.]</p>
<p>Elia: [to Avyanna] That complaint was posted six months ago. Couch still has the spring. But the complaint stays on the board until it&#x27;s resolved. Public reminder.</p>
<p>Rho: [defensive] I&#x27;m waiting on a parts shipment.</p>
<p>Elia: [flat] For six months.</p>
<p>Rho: [muttering] It&#x27;s a very specific spring.</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// CORRECTION: spring is standard-issue | RHO HAS SIMPLY NOT PRIORITIZED REQUISITION | RECEIPTS AVAILABLE&gt;</p>
<p>Rho: [to Bubbles] I&#x27;m going to disable your snark subroutines.</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// RESPONSE: you are not authorized | ALSO I DO NOT HAVE SNARK SUBROUTINES | I HAVE ACCURACY SUBROUTINES | THEY ARE VERY EFFECTIVE&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna watches the board scroll. Hundreds of entries. Some resolved. Some pending. Some just... observations about ship life.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [careful] What if someone posts something... mean?</p>
<p>Elia: [considering] Define mean.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Like... personal. Attacking someone.</p>
<p>Rho: [nodding] That&#x27;s against Sparkle rules. Complaints have to be about behavior, not identity. &quot;You&#x27;re lazy&quot; is not allowed. &quot;You didn&#x27;t complete the task you agreed to do&quot; is allowed.</p>
<p>Elia: [adding] And if someone does post an attack, the crew can flag it. If it&#x27;s flagged by three people, it gets reviewed. If it&#x27;s genuinely out of line, it&#x27;s removed and the poster gets a warning.</p>
<p>Elia: [meeting Avyanna&#x27;s eyes] Sparkle isn&#x27;t about cruelty. It&#x27;s about accountability. There&#x27;s a difference.</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// CLARIFICATION: sparkle doctrine is harm reduction for conflict | CONFLICT IS INEVITABLE AMONG HUMANS | QUESTION IS WHETHER CONFLICT ESCALATES TO VIOLENCE OR GETS DOCUMENTED AND RESOLVED | SPARKLE CHOOSES DOCUMENTATION&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] In the mine, if you complained, you got punished.</p>
<p>Rho: [somber] Yeah. That&#x27;s extraction logic. Keep people silent. Keep them compliant.</p>
<p>Rho: [gesturing at the board] Here, silence is suspicious. If no one&#x27;s complaining, either everything&#x27;s perfect-which is statistically impossible-or people are afraid to speak. We want complaints. They&#x27;re data.</p>
<p>Elia: [adding] I&#x27;ve worked on ships where complaints were forbidden. Where you had to smile and pretend everything was fine while systems failed and people got hurt.</p>
<p>Elia: [flat] Those ships were disasters. People quit. Or got injured. Or sabotaged things out of spite because they had no other outlet.</p>
<p>Elia: Here, you complain. It gets documented. It gets addressed or not addressed. But it&#x27;s visible. That&#x27;s the floor.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna absorbs this. Complaints as data. Conflict as normal. Documentation as protection.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] Can I... try posting something?</p>
<p>Rho: [surprised] Yeah. Absolutely. What&#x27;s your complaint?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [thinking] The... the shower in my quarters. The temperature control doesn&#x27;t work right. It&#x27;s either scalding or freezing. No in-between.</p>
<p>Rho: [wincing] Okay, that&#x27;s actually a problem. Why didn&#x27;t you mention it before?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] I thought... I thought I just had to deal with it.</p>
<p>Rho: [firm] No. You document it. Then I fix it. That&#x27;s how this works.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Elia hands Avyanna her datapad.]</p>
<p>Elia: [guiding] Open the Sparkle board. Hit &quot;new complaint.&quot; Fill in the fields. Description, location, priority. Then post.</p>
<p>[Avyanna takes the datapad. Her hands shake slightly. This feels like tattling. Like insubordination.]</p>
<p>[She types:]</p>
<p>**COMPLAINT #848: Shower temperature control in crew quarters 3B malfunctioning. Oscillates between scalding and freezing. Requesting repair. -Avyanna**</p>
<p>[She hesitates before hitting &quot;post.&quot;]</p>
<p>Rho: [gentle] It&#x27;s okay. You&#x27;re allowed to complain. No one&#x27;s going to punish you.</p>
<p>[Avyanna hits &quot;post.&quot; The complaint appears on the board.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho pulls out his own datapad. Types quickly. A response appears below her complaint:]</p>
<p>**RESPONSE TO #848: Acknowledged. Will inspect crew quarters 3B shower system within 24 hours. Likely thermostat calibration issue. -Rho**</p>
<p>Rho: [to Avyanna] See? You complained. I acknowledged. Now it&#x27;s on record that I&#x27;m supposed to fix it. If I don&#x27;t, you can complain again. Or escalate to Vesper.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [uncertain] You&#x27;re not... angry?</p>
<p>Rho: [laughing] Angry? Kid, I&#x27;m the ship&#x27;s engineer. Complaints are my job security. If nothing ever broke, I&#x27;d be useless.</p>
<p>Elia: [dry] You&#x27;re already useless.</p>
<p>Rho: [grinning] And yet, beloved.</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: trainee successfully posted first complaint | COMPLAINT VALID AND APPROPRIATELY FORMATTED | RESPONSE TIME: immediate | ASSESSMENT: trainee learning to use voice in conflict-resolution contexts&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares at the board. Her complaint is there. Public. Acknowledged. Not punished.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [whispered] This is... strange.</p>
<p>Elia: [nodding] It is. The mine taught you that speaking up is dangerous. Unlearning that takes time.</p>
<p>Elia: [meeting her eyes] But every time you post a complaint and nothing bad happens, your brain collects data. Eventually, it stops expecting punishment.</p>
<p>Rho: [standing, stretching] I&#x27;m gonna go fix that heating issue before Elia posts a follow-up complaint about my laziness.</p>
<p>Elia: [calm] Already drafting it.</p>
<p>Rho: [pointing at her] You&#x27;re the worst.</p>
<p>Elia: [slight smile] I know.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho leaves. Elia stays, scrolling through the board on her datapad.]</p>
<p>Elia: [after a moment] You know what the best part of Sparkle is?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [looking at her] What?</p>
<p>Elia: [quiet] It means you don&#x27;t have to carry everything alone. In the Wandering Market, if something bothered you, you swallowed it. Because who were you going to tell? Who cared?</p>
<p>Elia: [meeting her eyes] Here, you tell everyone. And someone cares. Maybe not everyone. But someone. And that&#x27;s enough.</p>
<p>[Avyanna nods slowly. The board is still glowing on the wall. Hundreds of small grievances and observations and requests. Proof that people speak. And people listen.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[She finishes her tea. Stands.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [to Elia] Thank you. For explaining.</p>
<p>Elia: [waving her off] Just doctrine. You&#x27;ll use it a hundred times. Might as well understand it now.</p>
<p>[Avyanna leaves the common room. In the corridor, she pauses. Pulls out her own datapad. Opens the Sparkle board. Scrolls through complaints, responses, observations.]</p>
<p>(People complain here. And it&#x27;s normal. And it&#x27;s safe.)</p>
<p>[The shard at the base of her skull is warm.]</p>
<p>(The hum at the base of her skull steadies: speak, record, safe.)</p>
<p>[She pockets the datapad and walks back to her quarters. Tomorrow, she&#x27;ll post another complaint. Or an observation. Or maybe just a thought.]</p>
<p>[And slowly, incrementally, she&#x27;s learning that her voice has a place here.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// SPARKLE BOARD LOG: trainee posted first complaint | RESPONSE TIME: 3.2 minutes | RESOLUTION STATUS: acknowledged, repair scheduled | ASSESSMENT: trainee engaging with crew conflict-resolution systems appropriately | STATUS: integration progressing&gt;</p>
<p>&lt;ELIA PERSONAL LOG: &quot;She looked terrified posting that complaint. Like she expected us to yell at her for having a broken shower. But she did it anyway. That&#x27;s courage. That&#x27;s growth.&quot;&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Scene*</p>
</div>

