:: Act1 18 Primordial Garden
<h1>Chapter 18: Primordial Garden</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 18_primordial_garden.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **SUTURED HOUSE VISITOR LOG - GARDEN-7 (RESTRICTED):** &gt; *Vessel: Lumen Thief, Registry 7742-KAEL* &gt; *Purpose: Training access (provisional)* &gt; *Duration: 36 hours standard* &gt; *Escort: Nyx Halden (House affiliate, lapsed)* &gt; *Note: The trainee carries something old. The garden will respond.* &gt; *Addendum: This is not a gift. This is a test.*</p>
<hr>
<p>[The station doesn&#x27;t look like much from the outside.]</p>
<p>[A converted asteroid, hollowed and pressurized, spinning slowly in a static-adjacent zone where most ships wouldn&#x27;t dare to anchor. The hull is old-pre-Compact construction, maybe older. No visible weapons. No obvious defenses.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna stands at the Lumen Thief&#x27;s viewport, watching the approach. The shard at the base of her skull is warm-not pain, not warning. Something else. Anticipation, maybe.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [beside her] They call it a Garden. One of the Sutured training grounds.</p>
<p>Avyanna: It doesn&#x27;t look like a garden.</p>
<p>Nyx: The garden is inside.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Docking is smooth. Jalen navigates the Thief through an approach corridor that feels wrong-angles that shouldn&#x27;t work, distances that don&#x27;t quite add up. The shard hums, translating something she can&#x27;t consciously perceive.]</p>
<p>[The airlock opens onto a receiving bay. Clean. Quiet. No armed guards-but a stone pedestal near the door holds a visitor&#x27;s log, real paper, and a stylus worn smooth from decades of use. A placard mounted above it reads: *Record your presence. Presence is consent.*]</p>
<p>[A single figure waits beside the log: an elderly person in simple robes, face weathered, eyes sharp. They gesture for Nyx to sign.]</p>
<p>[Nyx does, without complaint. Avyanna watches them write their name, the date, the ship registry-the same paperwork rituals she saw everywhere else, just rendered in older materials.]</p>
<p>Elder: [to Nyx] You&#x27;re late. Still.</p>
<p>Nyx: [dry] I&#x27;m always late. You still haven&#x27;t adjusted your expectations.</p>
<p>Elder: And you still haven&#x27;t come home. Three years lapsed now, is it?</p>
<p>Nyx: [carefully neutral] Four. But who&#x27;s counting.</p>
<p>[Something passes between them. Old familiarity. Old tension. Old fracture Avyanna can&#x27;t read.]</p>
<p>Elder: [looking at Avyanna] And this is the carrier.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [stiffening] My name is Avyanna.</p>
<p>Elder: [after a beat] Yes. It is.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The elder leads them through corridors that curve in directions they shouldn&#x27;t. The station&#x27;s geometry is wrong-not threatening, just different. Built according to rules Avyanna doesn&#x27;t know yet.]</p>
<p>[And then they step through a final door, and Avyanna stops breathing.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[The Garden is impossible.]</p>
<p>[A vast domed space, kilometers across, filled with growing things-trees, flowers, vines, organisms that aren&#x27;t quite plants and aren&#x27;t quite anything else. Light filters from above, soft and golden, from a sun that shouldn&#x27;t exist inside an asteroid.]</p>
<p>[The air is thick with scent: loam, chlorophyll, something sweeter underneath. The shard flares-not pain, not warning. *Recognition*. Like coming home to a place she&#x27;s never been.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [barely a whisper] How is this...</p>
<p>Nyx: [quiet] The Primordial Lattice. This is what it can do when it&#x27;s not being extracted from.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They walk through growing things. The path winds between cultivation plots, meditation circles, small structures that might be homes or temples or something in between.]</p>
<p>[Other practitioners are here-dozens of them, working in the gardens, sitting in circles, moving through exercises that look like dance and feel like something else. They&#x27;re all ages. All backgrounds. And they all look... healthy. Vital. None of the extraction damage Avyanna saw in the mine.]</p>
<p>Elder: [walking ahead] This garden has been maintained for three hundred years. Primordial methods only. No Synthetic extraction. No externalized costs.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [looking at the practitioners] They don&#x27;t age like-</p>
<p>Elder: Like mine workers? No. They age like humans are supposed to age. Slowly. With dignity. Without having their lives stolen to power someone else&#x27;s convenience.</p>
<p>[The words land like blows. Avyanna thinks of the woman in the mine who looked ancient at thirty-two. Thinks of the fifthieth birthday that was treated like a funeral joke.]</p>
<p>(This is what they took from us. This is what life is supposed to look like.)</p>
<hr>
<p>[The training area is a clearing at the garden&#x27;s center.]</p>
<p>[A circle of stones. A pool of still water. Trees whose branches form a natural dome overhead. At the entrance, a weathered sign reads: *DO NOT RUN HOT. Throughput limits protect everyone. Report discomfort immediately.* The warning looks decades old-safety placards, even here.]</p>
<p>[The shard is pulsing now-steady, rhythmic, almost excited.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [to the elder] The basic exercises. Grounding, perception, local boundary work.</p>
<p>Elder: [studying Avyanna] The shard will interfere. It&#x27;s already trying to communicate.</p>
<p>Nyx: That&#x27;s why we&#x27;re here. To give it context. To give *her* context.</p>
<p>[The elder nods. Turns to Avyanna.]</p>
<p>Elder: What do you know about what you&#x27;re carrying?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [careful] It&#x27;s Primordial. It&#x27;s old. It&#x27;s... waking up.</p>
<p>Elder: Did Nyx tell you what &quot;waking up&quot; means?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [glancing at Nyx] Not exactly.</p>
<p>Elder: [a thin smile] Good. Some things should be discovered, not explained.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The first exercise is simple: sit. Breathe. Feel the Lattice around her.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna settles onto one of the stones. The surface is warm, sun-heated, solid. She closes her eyes.]</p>
<p>[The shard responds immediately. Pressure behind her eyes. Geometric patterns at the edge of perception. Something trying to communicate in a language she doesn&#x27;t speak yet.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [nearby] Don&#x27;t fight it. Don&#x27;t chase it. Just notice.</p>
<p>[She tries. The patterns shift-fractals, spirals, shapes that fold through dimensions she can&#x27;t name. The shard is showing her something. Teaching her something. But the translation isn&#x27;t working yet.]</p>
<p>[Pain. Sharp. Sudden. She gasps, opens her eyes.]</p>
<p>Elder: [unsurprised] It tried too much too fast. The channel isn&#x27;t ready.</p>
<p>Nyx: [concerned] Avyanna-</p>
<p>Avyanna: [breathing hard] I&#x27;m okay. It&#x27;s just... loud.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They try again. Smaller this time. The elder guides her toward simple perception-not trying to use the Lattice, just feeling its presence.]</p>
<p>[The garden helps. Something about this place makes the shard calmer, more patient. The Primordial Lattice here is strong, stable, nurtured. It&#x27;s not fighting extraction damage or Synthetic interference.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna feels it: a vast, slow presence underneath everything. The substrate that reality runs on. It&#x27;s warm, patient, older than anything she has words for.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [eyes still closed] It&#x27;s... it&#x27;s like being inside something alive.</p>
<p>Elder: [approvingly] Yes. The Primordial Lattice is the galaxy&#x27;s nervous system. Not a tool to be used-a partner to be respected.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The second exercise is boundary work.]</p>
<p>Elder: Feel where you end and the Lattice begins. The edge of your presence. The limits of your locality.</p>
<p>[Avyanna tries. It&#x27;s harder than she expected. Her sense of self has always been... uncertain. In the mine, she learned to be invisible, to occupy as little space as possible. Now she&#x27;s being asked to feel her own edges.]</p>
<p>[The shard helps, unexpectedly. It maps her boundaries for her-here is Avyanna, here is not-Avyanna, here is the edge where they meet. The geometry is strange but stable.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [watching] Good. Now extend it. Not far-just a hand&#x27;s breadth. Feel the space around you as if it were part of you.</p>
<p>[She tries. The extension is clumsy, uncertain. But something happens-a shimmer at the edge of perception, a slight pressure in the air around her hands.]</p>
<p>Elder: [quiet] She&#x27;s a natural. The shard chose well.</p>
<p>Nyx: [also quiet] Or she chose the shard. We still don&#x27;t know which direction that went.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They break for food. The garden provides: fruit from trees Avyanna doesn&#x27;t recognize, bread baked in a communal oven, water that tastes like nothing she&#x27;s ever tasted-clean, mineral, alive.]</p>
<p>[She sits with Nyx on a stone bench, watching other practitioners move through their routines.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: They&#x27;re old.</p>
<p>Nyx: [glancing at her] Who?</p>
<p>Avyanna: The practitioners. Some of them. Old in a way I&#x27;ve never seen.</p>
<p>[She points to a figure across the clearing-a woman with silver hair, moving through a slow form with the grace of someone who&#x27;s been doing it for decades. Her face is lined but not weathered. Her body is aged but not broken.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: In the mine, no one looked like that. &quot;Fifty is a good run,&quot; they said. Like it was normal.</p>
<p>Nyx: [quietly] It&#x27;s not normal. It&#x27;s never been normal. The extraction makes people forget what human aging is supposed to look like.</p>
<hr>
<p>Avyanna: How old is the oldest person here?</p>
<p>Nyx: [considering] In this garden? Perhaps ninety. Ninety-five.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [staring] Ninety-five?</p>
<p>Nyx: The Primordial way doesn&#x27;t steal from practitioners. It works with them. Sustainable methods, sustainable lives.</p>
<p>[Nyx lets the number sit.]</p>
<p>Nyx: Someone is living longer than this. Much longer. We don&#x27;t know exactly how old, or how many. But the extraction economy isn&#x27;t running itself. It&#x27;s feeding something.</p>
<p>Avyanna: And everyone else pays.</p>
<p>Nyx: Everyone else pays.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They eat in silence for a few minutes.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna tries to make herself small on the bench. She fails. The garden makes smallness feel ridiculous-like crouching under a sky that wants you to stand.]</p>
<p>[Her fingers keep drifting back to the bread, to the fruit. Counting. Calculating.]</p>
<p>[She catches herself tucking an extra piece into her pocket. Habit. Scarcity math.]</p>
<p>[Nyx&#x27;s gaze flicks-not accusation. Not permission either. Just noticing.]</p>
<p>Nyx: You can take food.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [stiff] I wasn&#x27;t-</p>
<p>Nyx: I know.</p>
<p>[Nyx&#x27;s voice stays careful. Neutral enough not to trip shame.]</p>
<p>Nyx: The Kennel taught you that eating is a negotiation.</p>
<p>Nyx: Here, it&#x27;s maintenance.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Maintenance.</p>
<p>Nyx: Bodies are machines with feelings.</p>
<p>Nyx: If you run them on panic and caffeine and spite, they still run.</p>
<p>Nyx: For a while.</p>
<p>[Avyanna swallows.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: In the mine, if you got tired, it meant you were weak.</p>
<p>Nyx: In the mine, if you got tired, it meant you were human.</p>
<p>[A beat.]</p>
<p>Nyx: They called humanity weakness because it made you easier to manage.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s jaw tightens. The sentence is a lever inside her ribcage.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: So... when someone says &quot;that&#x27;s just the way bodies work,&quot; I should ask-</p>
<p>Nyx: Who profits from you believing that.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet, fierce] And what they&#x27;re hiding.</p>
<p>[Nyx&#x27;s mouth twitches. Not quite a smile. Something like approval.]</p>
<p>Nyx: Yes.</p>
<p>[Avyanna stares across the clearing at the older practitioners again. The ones who look... intact.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: If this is possible, why doesn&#x27;t everyone-</p>
<p>Nyx: Because &quot;possible&quot; is not the same as &quot;allowed.&quot;</p>
<p>Nyx: Because the people who benefit from extraction also control the education.</p>
<p>[Nyx taps the edge of Avyanna&#x27;s pocket with two fingers-light, not touching her skin.]</p>
<p>Nyx: Eat when you&#x27;re hungry.</p>
<p>Nyx: Rest when you&#x27;re tired.</p>
<p>Nyx: Not as a reward.</p>
<p>Nyx: As a refusal.</p>
<p>[Avyanna sits with that. Rest as refusal. Food as refusal. Her body as a thing that belongs to her, not a schedule.]</p>
<p>[The afternoon brings harder exercises.]</p>
<p>[The elder has Avyanna attempt local influence-not magic in the Synthetic sense, but relationship with the Lattice. Asking, not demanding. Suggesting, not forcing.]</p>
<p>[She tries to move a pebble. Not with force-with invitation. Extending her presence, making space for the pebble to shift, offering a destination without insisting.]</p>
<p>[Nothing happens.]</p>
<p>[Nothing happens for a long time.]</p>
<p>Elder: [patient] You&#x27;re still thinking like a Synthetic user. You&#x27;re trying to make the Lattice do what you want.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [frustrated] How else would I-</p>
<p>Elder: Ask. Wait. Accept the answer, whatever it is.</p>
<hr>
<p>[She tries again. And again. The shard pulses, patient, observing.]</p>
<p>[On the fifteenth attempt, something shifts. The pebble doesn&#x27;t move-but she feels something. A response. A presence noticing her request and considering it.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [eyes widening] It&#x27;s... it&#x27;s thinking about it?</p>
<p>Elder: [almost smiling] The Lattice isn&#x27;t mechanical. It&#x27;s relational. Every interaction is a conversation.</p>
<p>Nyx: [to the elder] The shard is translating for her. She shouldn&#x27;t be perceiving that clearly yet.</p>
<p>Elder: [studying Avyanna] No. She shouldn&#x27;t.</p>
<hr>
<p>[By evening, Avyanna is exhausted.]</p>
<p>[The kind of tired that goes deeper than muscles-the fatigue of learning to use parts of herself she didn&#x27;t know existed. The shard is quiet now, processing, integrating. It&#x27;s worked as hard as she has.]</p>
<p>[Nyx finds her sitting by the pool, watching the water reflect the garden&#x27;s false sunset.]</p>
<p>Nyx: How do you feel?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [honestly] Overwhelmed. Also... hopeful?</p>
<p>Nyx: [sitting beside her] Why hopeful?</p>
<p>Avyanna: Because this exists. All of this.</p>
<p>[She gestures at the garden. The practitioners. The impossible, sustainable, beautiful proof that another way is possible.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: In the mine, I thought short lives were just... how it worked. Physics. Economics. The way reality was structured. But this-</p>
<p>[She stops. Tries again.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: This means they *chose* to make it worse. The extraction. The theft. All of it. They chose it when they could have chosen this.</p>
<hr>
<p>Nyx: [quietly] Yes.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s... that&#x27;s worse, isn&#x27;t it? Knowing it was a choice.</p>
<p>Nyx: Is it? I find it clarifying.</p>
<p>[Avyanna looks at them. Waiting.]</p>
<p>Nyx: If it were physics-if extraction were truly the only way-we&#x27;d have nothing to fight against. Just entropy. Just the way things are.</p>
<p>[They gesture at the garden.]</p>
<p>Nyx: But this proves it&#x27;s not physics. It&#x27;s policy. And policies can be changed.</p>
<hr>
<p>[That night, Avyanna sleeps in a guest chamber that feels more like a cave-carved stone, living moss, air that smells of growing things. The shard settles into something like contentment.]</p>
<p>[She dreams of gardens. Of time that isn&#x27;t stolen. Of bodies that age with dignity and lives that extend into decades she never imagined.]</p>
<p>[And underneath the dreams, a voice that isn&#x27;t quite a voice. A presence that isn&#x27;t quite present yet. Something old, patient, learning alongside her.]</p>
<p>[The shape of waiting. The geometry of almost-ready.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Morning brings departure.]</p>
<p>[The elder walks them back to the docking bay. The path seems shorter than before-the station adjusting itself, maybe, or Avyanna perceiving it differently.]</p>
<p>Elder: [to Avyanna] The shard in you is preparing for something. When it fully manifests, remember what you learned here.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Locality. Throughput. Consent.</p>
<p>Elder: [nodding] And one more thing.</p>
<p>[They stop at the airlock. Turn to face Avyanna directly.]</p>
<p>Elder: The conservation law is a lie. But the truth underneath it is dangerous. Don&#x27;t burn hot. Don&#x27;t try to scale. The Primordial way is slow because slowness protects everyone-including you.</p>
<p>Avyanna: I understand.</p>
<p>Elder: [studying her] Perhaps. We&#x27;ll see.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Back on the Lumen Thief, Avyanna stands at the viewport and watches the Garden station recede.]</p>
<p>[The shard hums. Not pain. Not warning. Something like promise.]</p>
<p>(There&#x27;s another way. The extraction isn&#x27;t the only path. The costs can be sustainable.)</p>
<p>[She thinks of the practitioners moving through their routines. The woman with the graceful form who might be ninety-five. The garden that had been maintained for three centuries without destroying anyone.]</p>
<p>(Someone built a machine to steal life from everyone else. But this place proves the machine isn&#x27;t the only option.)</p>
<p>[The thought is too big. She puts it aside. There will be time later to think about galaxy-scale problems.]</p>
<p>[For now, she has exercises to practice. Boundaries to feel. A shard to work with instead of against.]</p>
<p>[For now, that&#x27;s enough.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: trainee returned from Garden-7 with altered perception patterns | INFERENCE: training effective | CONFIDENCE: 0.86 | NOTE: flagging for Nyx re: accelerated perceptual development. may require adjusted curriculum.&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Chapter 18*</p>
</div>

