:: Act1 18b Station Overwhelm Recovery
<h1>Optional 18b: Station Overwhelm Recovery</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 18b_station_overwhelm_recovery.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH18, DURING EXTENDED STATION LAYOVER]** &gt; *Location: Station public area -&gt; quiet zone -&gt; ship* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Waffle, later Nyx* &gt; *Teaching: Recognizing limits, self-advocacy, recovery without shame*</p>
<hr>
<p>[Station Helix-9 is crowded. More crowded than Avyanna expected. More crowded than she can handle.]</p>
<p>[She&#x27;s been walking through the market district for twenty minutes. Waffle hovers beside her, scanning for threats, maintaining a polite bubble of space around her. But the crowd is pressing in anyway. Too many bodies. Too many voices. Too much motion and light and sound.]</p>
<p>[Her breathing is getting shallow. Her vision is narrowing. The edges are going gray.]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ALERT: trainee exhibiting physiological stress markers | HEART RATE: elevated | RESPIRATION: shallow and rapid | RECOMMENDATION: extraction to low-stimulation environment&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna doesn&#x27;t respond. She&#x27;s trying to push through it. Trying to function. If she stops now, if she asks to leave, she&#x27;s failing. She&#x27;s weak. She&#x27;s-]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// OVERRIDE: trainee nonresponsive to verbal | IMPLEMENTING EMERGENCY GROUNDING PROTOCOL&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Waffle projects a bright light pattern directly in front of Avyanna&#x27;s face. Geometric. Rhythmic. Impossible to ignore.]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ATTENTION: you are experiencing sensory overload | THIS IS NOT FAILURE | THIS IS BIOLOGY | INSTRUCTION: follow me to quiet zone | DURATION: two minutes&gt;</p>
<p>[The light pattern moves. Slowly. Waffle is guiding her.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna follows because following is easier than deciding. Her legs move. Waffle carves a path through the crowd with surprising authority-people step aside for the Guild drone without complaint.]</p>
<p>[Two minutes later, they&#x27;re in a quiet zone. A designated low-stimulation area. Dimmed lights. Soundproofing. Soft seating. Empty except for one person sleeping in a corner.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Waffle hovers beside a bench.]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// INSTRUCTION: sit | FOCUS ON LIGHT PATTERN | BREATHE: in for four, hold for four, out for four | I AM HERE | YOU ARE SAFE&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna sits. Her hands are shaking. Her vision is still gray at the edges. But the noise is gone. The crowd is gone. There&#x27;s just quiet and Waffle&#x27;s light pattern and the instruction to breathe.]</p>
<p>[In for four. Hold. Out for four.]</p>
<p>[In for four. Hold. Out for four.]</p>
<p>[Her vision clears incrementally. The gray recedes. Her heart rate slows.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// OBSERVATION: panic attack in progress, moderate severity | RESPONSE: extracted to safe environment | STATUS: trainee stabilizing | DURATION: will monitor&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna focuses on the light. On the counting. On Waffle&#x27;s steady presence.]</p>
<p>[After five minutes, she can speak.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hoarse] I&#x27;m sorry.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// CORRECTION: you have nothing to apologize for | SENSORY OVERLOAD IS EXPECTED POST-TRAUMA RESPONSE | YOU RECOGNIZED DISTRESS | YOU ACCEPTED ASSISTANCE | THIS IS APPROPRIATE BEHAVIOR&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking] I should be able to handle crowds. It&#x27;s just people. It&#x27;s not dangerous.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// CORRECTION: danger is subjective | YOUR NERVOUS SYSTEM ASSESSED THREAT BASED ON AVAILABLE DATA | CROWDS = UNPREDICTABLE = HIGH COGNITIVE LOAD = PERCEIVED DANGER | YOUR BODY RESPONDED APPROPRIATELY TO PERCEIVED THREAT&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna sits with that. Her body isn&#x27;t wrong. It&#x27;s just responding to old data.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] How long until I can handle this?</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ANSWER: variable | TRAUMA RECOVERY IS NONLINEAR | SOME DAYS YOU WILL TOLERATE CROWDS | SOME DAYS YOU WILL NOT | THIS IS NORMAL | THE GOAL IS NOT PERFECTION | THE GOAL IS RECOGNIZING YOUR LIMITS AND RESPONDING APPROPRIATELY&gt;</p>
<p>[Waffle&#x27;s lights pulse gently.]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ADDENDUM: you could have remained in the crowd and dissociated | MANY TRAUMA SURVIVORS DO | YOU ACCEPTED EXTRACTION INSTEAD | THAT IS PROGRESS&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [uncertain] It doesn&#x27;t feel like progress.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// RESPONSE: progress rarely feels like progress while it is happening | PROGRESS FEELS LIKE SURVIVING | YOU ARE SURVIVING | THEREFORE YOU ARE PROGRESSING&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[They sit in the quiet zone for fifteen minutes. Avyanna breathes. Waffle maintains its light pattern and proximity. No judgment. No impatience. Just presence.]</p>
<p>[Eventually, Avyanna&#x27;s hands stop shaking.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [to Waffle] Can we go back to the ship?</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// AFFIRMATIVE: return route optimized for minimal crowd exposure | DURATION: eight minutes | QUERY: do you require additional support or are you functional for transit&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [standing slowly] I can walk. I just... I need to not be on the station anymore.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ACKNOWLEDGED: extracting to lumen thief | PROCEDURE: stay within two meters | IF DISTRESS RECURS, SIGNAL AND I WILL ADJUST ROUTE&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[They leave the quiet zone. Waffle navigates them through service corridors instead of main concourses. Fewer people. Less noise. The route is longer, but safer for Avyanna&#x27;s nervous system.]</p>
<p>[She focuses on Waffle&#x27;s back. On following. On breathing. On not thinking about how she failed to handle a simple station visit.]</p>
<p>[Eight minutes later, they reach the ship&#x27;s airlock. The door hisses closed behind them. Station noise cuts off. Ship sounds resume-familiar hum of life support, the steady rhythm of systems that don&#x27;t change unpredictably.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s shoulders drop two inches.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// OBSERVATION: trainee relaxation response upon returning to ship environment | INFERENCE: ship is perceived as safe space | CONFIDENCE: 0.92 | THIS IS APPROPRIATE | HOME SHOULD FEEL SAFER THAN EXTERNAL ENVIRONMENTS&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Thank you. For getting me out.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// RESPONSE: that is crew function | YOU WOULD DO THE SAME FOR ME IF I WERE IN DISTRESS | MUTUAL AID IS STRUCTURAL, NOT TRANSACTIONAL&gt;</p>
<p>[Waffle hovers beside her as she walks to her quarters. She expects Waffle to leave. It doesn&#x27;t.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [at her door] I&#x27;m okay now. You don&#x27;t have to stay.</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// CORRECTION: you are stabilized, not okay | DISTINCTION MATTERS | I WILL NOTIFY NYX OF INCIDENT PER MEDICAL PROTOCOL | THEY MAY WISH TO CHECK IN&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [tense] You&#x27;re reporting me?</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// CLARIFICATION: i am documenting a medical event | NOT FOR PUNISHMENT | FOR CARE | NYX WILL ASSESS WHETHER ADDITIONAL SUPPORT IS NEEDED | IF YOU WISH TO DECLINE ASSESSMENT, THAT IS YOUR RIGHT | BUT I RECOMMEND ACCEPTANCE&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna sits on her bunk. Waffle hovers near the door-present but not crowding.]</p>
<p>[Five minutes later, Nyx arrives. Knocks. Waits for permission.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [tired] Come in.</p>
<p>[Nyx enters. Sits in the desk chair. Doesn&#x27;t loom.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [calm] Waffle says you had a panic attack on station. Are you injured?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [shaking her head] No. Just... overwhelmed.</p>
<p>Nyx: [nodding] Station sensory overload. Common. How are you feeling now?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [honest] Tired. Embarrassed. Angry at myself.</p>
<p>Nyx: [precise] Tired is expected. Panic attacks are exhausting. Embarrassed and angry are optional and unhelpful.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna looks up. Nyx&#x27;s expression is neutral. Clinical. Not judging.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [continuing] You encountered a stimulus your nervous system couldn&#x27;t process. You recognized distress. You accepted assistance. You extracted to safety. You recovered.</p>
<p>Nyx: [meeting her eyes] That&#x27;s not failure. That&#x27;s textbook appropriate response to overwhelm.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [frustrated] I should be able to handle a crowded station. It&#x27;s not dangerous.</p>
<p>Nyx: [flat] Your nervous system doesn&#x27;t care about objective danger. It cares about perceived danger. And for someone who spent years in an environment where crowds meant violence and unpredictability meant punishment, a crowded station *is* dangerous. To your nervous system, that&#x27;s truth.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Nyx pulls out a medical scanner. Waves it near Avyanna without touching her.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [reading] Elevated cortisol. Adrenaline still clearing. Heart rate returning to baseline. You&#x27;re recovering appropriately.</p>
<p>[They put the scanner away.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [leaning forward slightly] Here&#x27;s what I&#x27;m prescribing. Not medication. Just protocol.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [wary] Protocol?</p>
<p>Nyx: [listing] One: You rest for the next two hours. No tasks. No obligations. Just recovery.</p>
<p>Nyx: Two: If you feel up to it, you eat something. Your body burned a lot of resources during that panic response. Food helps replenish.</p>
<p>Nyx: Three: You do not punish yourself for having limits. Limits are information, not failure.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Avyanna processes that. Limits as information.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] What if I can&#x27;t do the next station visit? What if this keeps happening?</p>
<p>Nyx: [measured] Then we adjust. Shorter visits. Different times of day when stations are less crowded. Backup plans for extraction. Grounding tools.</p>
<p>Nyx: [meeting her eyes] Your nervous system is healing. Healing isn&#x27;t linear. Some days you&#x27;ll tolerate more. Some days you&#x27;ll tolerate less. We adapt to what you can handle on a given day. That&#x27;s not weakness. That&#x27;s strategy.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [uncertain] The crew won&#x27;t think I&#x27;m... useless?</p>
<p>Nyx: [dry] The crew thinks you&#x27;re a trainee recovering from severe trauma who&#x27;s learning to identify and respond to your limits. That&#x27;s exactly what we expect you to be.</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// ADDENDUM: crew has experience with trauma recovery | ELIA HAD SIMILAR SENSORY OVERWHELM FIRST YEAR ABOARD | JALEN STILL AVOIDS CERTAIN STATION SECTORS DUE TO COMPACT PTSD | YOU ARE NOT UNIQUE IN HAVING LIMITS | YOU ARE JUST LEARNING TO NAME THEM&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna looks at Waffle. Then at Nyx.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [slowly] Other crew have panic attacks?</p>
<p>Nyx: [nodding] Yes. Different triggers. Different presentations. But everyone on this ship has had moments where their nervous system said &quot;no more.&quot; You&#x27;re not alone in this.</p>
<p>Nyx: [standing] I&#x27;m going to make you tea. You&#x27;re going to drink it. Then you&#x27;re going to rest. In two hours, I&#x27;ll check on you again. If you need anything before then, you tell Waffle or use ship comms.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Thank you.</p>
<p>Nyx: [at the door] Thank Waffle. They executed the extraction perfectly.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Nyx leaves. Waffle remains.]</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// OBSERVATION: you are processing | THIS IS APPROPRIATE | QUERY: do you require continued presence or do you prefer solitude&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [considering] Stay? For a little while?</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// AFFIRMATIVE: i will remain | I WILL DIM MY LIGHTS TO NON-DISTRACTING LEVEL | I WILL MONITOR FOR DISTRESS | YOU MAY SLEEP IF YOU WISH | I WILL ENSURE YOU ARE NOT DISTURBED&gt;</p>
<p>[Waffle dims its lights. Hovers near the ceiling. Present but unobtrusive.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna lies back on her bunk. Her body is heavy with exhaustion. Her mind is quieter now. The panic is gone. The shame is lessening.]</p>
<p>(I had a panic attack. Waffle extracted me. Nyx checked on me. No one punished me. No one called me weak.)</p>
<p>[The shard at the base of her skull is warm.]</p>
<p>(A warm pressure at the base of her skull: limit, named, safe.)</p>
<hr>
<p>[She sleeps. Waffle keeps watch. Two hours later, Nyx returns with tea and a light meal. Avyanna wakes, eats, drinks. Feels more human.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [sitting] How are you feeling?</p>
<p>Avyanna: [honest] Better. Still tired. But better.</p>
<p>Nyx: [nodding] Good. Tomorrow, we talk about grounding techniques for managing sensory overload before it becomes full panic. For now, you rest.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [hesitant] What if there&#x27;s another station visit soon?</p>
<p>Nyx: [calm] Then we plan for it. Shorter duration. Specific objectives. Exit strategies. We don&#x27;t throw you into situations you&#x27;re not ready for. We build capacity gradually.</p>
<p>[Nyx stands.]</p>
<p>Nyx: [at the door] You did well today. You recognized you were in distress. You accepted help. You recovered. That&#x27;s not failure. That&#x27;s exactly what we need you to do.</p>
<hr>
<p>[After Nyx leaves, Avyanna sits with that. Not failure. Appropriate response. Limits as information, not inadequacy.]</p>
<p>[Tomorrow, she&#x27;ll learn grounding techniques. She&#x27;ll practice identifying overwhelm earlier. She&#x27;ll build tools for managing the unpredictable galaxy outside the ship.]</p>
<p>[But tonight, she rests. And that&#x27;s enough.]</p>
<hr>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// MEDICAL INCIDENT LOG: trainee experienced sensory overload event on station | WAFFLE EXTRACTION PROTOCOL: executed successfully | NYX ASSESSMENT: no injury, appropriate recovery | FOLLOW-UP: grounding techniques training scheduled | STATUS: incident resolved without complication&gt;</p>
<p>&lt;WAFFLE.BAT// PERSONAL NOTE: trainee accepted extraction without extended resistance | TRAINEE ACCEPTED MEDICAL ASSESSMENT | TRAINEE RESTING | THIS IS PROGRESS | SENSORY OVERLOAD WILL RECUR BUT TRAINEE NOW HAS EXPERIENCE WITH SUCCESSFUL RECOVERY PROTOCOL | CONFIDENCE: 0.89&gt;</p>
<p>&lt;NYX PERSONAL LOG: &quot;Panic attack. Standard post-trauma presentation. She&#x27;s learning that her nervous system is allowed to have limits. That those limits don&#x27;t disqualify her from crew. Tomorrow we work on prevention and early intervention. But today was about learning that recovery is possible. She learned.&quot;&gt;</p>
<hr>
<p>*End Scene*</p>
</div>

