:: Act1 20c Archive Ritual
<h1>Optional 20c: Archive Ritual</h1>
<p class="source-note">Source: 20c_archive_ritual.md</p>
<div class="scene-prose">
<p>&gt; **[SCENE - OCCURS POST-CH20, AFTER THE HEARING&#x27;S AFTERTASTE]** &gt; *Location: Vesper&#x27;s office / atrium board* &gt; *Present: Avyanna, Vesper; crew cameo; AI citizens assist* &gt; *Teaching: &quot;receipts survive people&quot; is a doctrine; belonging can be procedural*</p>
<hr>
<p>[After the hearing, the ship goes quiet in the way it does after violence that didn&#x27;t leave bruises.]</p>
<p>[Not silence. A hush.]</p>
<p>[The kind of hush that says: everybody is holding their own parts so no one drops.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna stands outside Vesper&#x27;s office with her hands full of paper.]</p>
<p>[Copies. Originals. A stack that looks like a weapon if you squint.]</p>
<p>(Paper can be burned.)</p>
<p>(Paper can also burn someone else.)</p>
<p>[Vesper opens the door before Avyanna knocks.]</p>
<p>Vesper: You&#x27;re hovering.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [automatic] Sorry.</p>
<p>[She stops.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: I am hovering.</p>
<p>[Vesper&#x27;s mouth twitches-approval that refuses to be cute.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Come in.</p>
<hr>
<p>[The office is the same as always: clean lines, sharp corners, a desk that looks like it has never forgiven anyone.]</p>
<p>[Vesper clears a space.]</p>
<p>[Not by sweeping things aside. By moving them to exact locations like the room has a map only she can see.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Set them there.</p>
<p>[Avyanna sets the stack down carefully, as if the paper is glass.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: What happens now.</p>
<p>Vesper: Now we make it heavy.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Heavy.</p>
<p>Vesper: So it can&#x27;t be erased by one bored clerk.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Cinnamon&#x27;s terminal wakes without being prompted, like she heard the word erased and took it personally.]</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// OBSERVATION: new evidence bundle present | ACTION: generate archive hashes | NOTE: I enjoy permanence&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: You enjoy permanence.</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// RESPONSE: yes | ADDENDUM: hostile systems rely on your belief that nothing persists&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna swallows.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Cinnamon, print chain-of-custody forms. Seven copies.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Seven.</p>
<p>Vesper: Three is minimum. Seven is insurance against sabotage.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s... a lot.</p>
<p>Vesper: It&#x27;s the point.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Vesper takes out a stamp.]</p>
<p>[A physical stamp. Metal. Heavy. The kind of tool that feels like law even when it&#x27;s just ink.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Do we have authority to-</p>
<p>Vesper: Under the Guild&#x27;s own procedures, yes.</p>
<p>Vesper: Under the Compact&#x27;s desire to pretend this never happened, no.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Then why-</p>
<p>Vesper: Because authority is not a moral property.</p>
<p>Vesper: It&#x27;s a lever.</p>
<p>[Avyanna watches her stamp the first page.]</p>
<p>*THUD.*</p>
<p>[Ink blooms: RECEIPT ACKNOWLEDGED.]</p>
<p>[The sound makes Avyanna flinch.]</p>
<p>(In the mine, stamps meant &quot;processed.&quot; Stamps meant &quot;unavoidable.&quot;)</p>
<p>[This stamp feels like something else.]</p>
<p>Vesper: You do the next one.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands freeze.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Me?</p>
<p>Vesper: Yes.</p>
<p>Avyanna: What if I do it wrong.</p>
<p>Vesper: Then we redo it.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s it.</p>
<p>Vesper: That&#x27;s it.</p>
<p>[Avyanna takes the stamp.]</p>
<p>[It is heavier than she expected.]</p>
<p>[She presses down.]</p>
<p>*THUD.*</p>
<p>[RECEIPT ACKNOWLEDGED.]</p>
<p>[She stares at it.]</p>
<p>(My hand made that.)</p>
<p>[Her throat tightens.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Good.</p>
<hr>
<p>[They work.]</p>
<p>[Vesper narrates without making it feel like a test.]</p>
<p>Vesper: Claim summary on top. Evidence list behind. Witness statements separated and indexed. Video hashes in the sealed envelope.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why separate.</p>
<p>Vesper: So if someone attacks a witness, the evidence survives them.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s stomach turns.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s... bleak.</p>
<p>Vesper: It&#x27;s reality.</p>
<p>Vesper: The way we make it less bleak is we don&#x27;t pretend.</p>
<p>[Avyanna nods and keeps stamping.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[A soft chime at the door.]</p>
<p>[Elisira slips in, silent as policy.]</p>
<p>Elisira: How&#x27;s the archive.</p>
<p>Vesper: In progress.</p>
<p>Elisira: Good.</p>
<p>[Elisira sets a small device on the desk-an external storage brick, scuffed and ordinary.]</p>
<p>Elisira: Offline copy. Air-gapped.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why.</p>
<p>Elisira: Because networks can be bribed.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] And paper can be burned.</p>
<p>Elisira: Yes.</p>
<p>Elisira: So we do both.</p>
<p>[Elisira&#x27;s gaze flicks to Avyanna.]</p>
<p>Elisira: You held yourself in the room.</p>
<p>Avyanna: I almost didn&#x27;t.</p>
<p>Elisira: Almost is not the outcome.</p>
<p>[She leaves without ceremony, like approval is a tool to be deployed precisely.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Rho appears next.]</p>
<p>[He leans in the doorway with coffee and the expression of someone pretending he&#x27;s not here to check on the kid.]</p>
<p>Rho: Heard you made the clerk blink.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [blinking] I-</p>
<p>Vesper: [without looking up] She did.</p>
<p>Rho: Nice.</p>
<p>[He sets a mug down next to Avyanna&#x27;s elbow.]</p>
<p>[Not asking if she wants it. Not demanding gratitude. Just placing warmth in the area.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Thank you.</p>
<p>Rho: [gruff] Yeah.</p>
<p>[He looks at the stacks.]</p>
<p>Rho: That&#x27;s a lot of paper.</p>
<p>Vesper: It&#x27;s not paper. It&#x27;s weight.</p>
<p>Rho: [snorts] Okay, philosopher.</p>
<p>Vesper: [flat] Don&#x27;t start.</p>
<p>[Rho leaves before the coffee becomes a conversation.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Elia arrives like she can&#x27;t stand the idea of quiet being too serious for too long.]</p>
<p>Elia: Are we doing paperwork violence.</p>
<p>Vesper: Yes.</p>
<p>Elia: Delicious.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [startled laugh] That&#x27;s-</p>
<p>Elia: A joke. Also true.</p>
<p>[Elia leans over the desk, reads a page, and her face changes.]</p>
<p>[Not joking now. Focused.]</p>
<p>Elia: [quiet] They wrote her up as &quot;noncompliant&quot; for refusing a sedative.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Yes.</p>
<p>Elia: I want to bite someone.</p>
<p>Vesper: Put it in the queue.</p>
<p>Elia: [bright again] Great. I love queues.</p>
<p>[She reaches out, hesitates, then taps Avyanna&#x27;s shoulder with one knuckle-light, careful.]</p>
<p>Elia: You did good, Avy.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s not a metric.</p>
<p>Elia: It is my metric.</p>
<p>[Elia points at the stamp.]</p>
<p>Elia: Can I stamp something.</p>
<p>Vesper: No.</p>
<p>Elia: Cruel.</p>
<p>Vesper: Necessary.</p>
<p>[Elia exits with a dramatic sigh, leaving behind the faint smell of mischief like a promise.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Bubbles drifts in last.]</p>
<p>[She doesn&#x27;t speak at first.]</p>
<p>[She watches Avyanna stamp and stack and index.]</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: trainee performing archival labor | INFERENCE: belonging increasing via contribution | CONFIDENCE: 0.84&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet, to Bubbles] Is this... crew work.</p>
<p>Bubbles: Yes.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Even though it&#x27;s just... paper.</p>
<p>Bubbles: Paper is how hostile systems pretend they are not hostile.</p>
<p>Bubbles: We use paper to make them show their teeth.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>(We make them show their teeth.)</p>
<p>[Vesper seals the final envelope with a strip that changes color when broken.]</p>
<p>Vesper: That&#x27;s it.</p>
<p>Avyanna: That&#x27;s it.</p>
<p>[She waits for the crash.]</p>
<p>[For someone to say: you did not do enough.]</p>
<p>[Instead, Vesper slides a copy folder toward her.]</p>
<p>Vesper: This one is yours.</p>
<p>Avyanna: Why.</p>
<p>Vesper: Because you are a witness.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s hands hover over the folder.]</p>
<p>(Mine taught me witnesses get punished.)</p>
<p>[She takes it anyway.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[They leave the office together.]</p>
<p>[In the atrium, there is a public board with a section labeled RECEIPTS.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna has seen other entries there: small disputes, supply issues, petty injustices documented in neat lines.]</p>
<p>[Vesper pins one sanitized summary-no names that would get someone killed, just the shape of the crime and the evidence that it happened.]</p>
<p>Vesper: [low] We don&#x27;t do this to be liked.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] We do it because it&#x27;s true.</p>
<p>Vesper: Yes.</p>
<p>[A few crew members pause as they pass.]</p>
<p>[They read.]</p>
<p>[They don&#x27;t clap. They don&#x27;t cheer.]</p>
<p>[They nod-like a vow acknowledged without noise.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna stands beside Vesper and watches her own life become a public weight the mine can&#x27;t lift easily.]</p>
<p>(This is what it feels like to have proof.)</p>
<p>[The ship hums around them, holding the moment without trying to own it.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[Later, Avyanna takes her copy folder back to her quarters.]</p>
<p>[She sets it on the small desk like it might bite.]</p>
<p>[Then she opens it anyway.]</p>
<p>[The first page is the sanitized summary Vesper pinned. The second is the internal index. The third is her own witness statement-her words, typed cleanly, no mine stutter, no apologies baked in.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna reads it three times.]</p>
<p>(If this existed when I was eight, would it have saved anyone.)</p>
<p>[Her throat tightens.]</p>
<p>[She reaches for her notebook and writes another claim.]</p>
<p>&gt; **CLAIM:** I am allowed to survive.</p>
<p>[She stares at it.]</p>
<p>(Allowed by whom.)</p>
<p>[She writes the next line carefully.]</p>
<p>&gt; **ENFORCED BY:** us.</p>
<p>[It looks childish.]</p>
<p>[It looks like the truth anyway.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[A notification pings on her terminal.]</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// MESSAGE: archive replication complete | COPIES: 7 | LOCATION: distributed | NOTE: erasure now expensive&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: [muttering] Good.</p>
<p>[She sits back.]</p>
<p>[The quiet in her room is different now.]</p>
<p>[Not empty. Not waiting.]</p>
<p>[Held.]</p>
<p>[She can hear distant voices in the atrium-Elia laughing too loud, Rho complaining about the coffee machine like it&#x27;s a moral failing, Waffle&#x27;s text chattering across a screen somewhere.]</p>
<p>[For a moment, the mine tries to overlay that sound with its own: sirens, boots, supervisors shouting numbers.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s body tenses.]</p>
<p>[Then she remembers the stamp.]</p>
<p>*THUD.*</p>
<p>[Receipt acknowledged.]</p>
<p>[She breathes until the mine recedes.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[She slips the copy folder into the bottom drawer of her desk.]</p>
<p>[Not hiding it.]</p>
<p>[Storing it like something that will still be there when she needs it.]</p>
<p>[She looks at the door.]</p>
<p>[Still open, as ship policy.]</p>
<p>[She doesn&#x27;t close it.]</p>
<p>[But for the first time, she doesn&#x27;t stare at it like it&#x27;s a countdown either.]</p>
<p>(I don&#x27;t have to be ready to run every second.)</p>
<p>[She lies down.]</p>
<p>[The pillow smells like clean fabric instead of dust.]</p>
<p>[Her hands still tremble, but less.]</p>
<p>[She falls asleep with the ugly, miraculous weight of proof in the drawer and the knowledge that the ship will keep humming whether she&#x27;s awake to guard it or not.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[When she wakes, the first thing her body does is listen.]</p>
<p>[Not for sirens.]</p>
<p>[For the ship.]</p>
<p>[A steady hum. Footsteps in the corridor. A door hiss somewhere distant.]</p>
<p>[No shouting. No quota bell. No supervisor voice turning time into threat.]</p>
<p>[Her shoulders unclench one notch at a time.]</p>
<p>(I slept.)</p>
<p>[She sits up and waits for the panic that usually follows sleep.]</p>
<p>[It comes, but smaller. Late. Like the mine is running out of power.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna touches the back of her neck where her old tag used to itch.]</p>
<p>[Then she stands and opens the drawer.]</p>
<p>[The folder is still there.]</p>
<p>[The paper didn&#x27;t vanish overnight. No one &quot;processed&quot; it away while she wasn&#x27;t looking.]</p>
<p>[She closes the drawer again, not because she&#x27;s hiding it-because she&#x27;s practicing treating permanence as normal.]</p>
<hr>
<p>[In the galley, Rho is already at war with the coffee machine.]</p>
<p>Rho: [to the machine] You are a liar and a coward.</p>
<p>Elia: [from the counter] It&#x27;s just a machine.</p>
<p>Rho: It knows what it did.</p>
<p>[Avyanna pauses in the doorway, watching the scene like it&#x27;s a documentary about a species she&#x27;s joining.]</p>
<p>(They argue and nobody dies.)</p>
<p>[Bubbles notices her first, as usual.]</p>
<p>Bubbles: Good morning.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] Morning.</p>
<p>[Rho turns, squints at her the way he squints at broken parts.]</p>
<p>Rho: You sleep.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [blinking] Yes.</p>
<p>Rho: Good.</p>
<p>[He pushes a plate toward her without asking.]</p>
<p>[Eggs. Toast. Something green that might be an herb and not a punishment.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [tight] I didn&#x27;t-</p>
<p>Rho: Eat.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [catching herself] Why.</p>
<p>Rho: Because you&#x27;re alive and it&#x27;s morning and you don&#x27;t have to earn breakfast.</p>
<p>[Avyanna&#x27;s throat tightens.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: Okay.</p>
<p>[She sits.]</p>
<p>[She eats one bite.]</p>
<p>[Her body waits for the ledger to appear and demand repayment.]</p>
<p>[Nothing happens.]</p>
<p>[Elia watches her chew like it&#x27;s a magic trick.]</p>
<p>Elia: See. The ship didn&#x27;t explode because you accepted food.</p>
<p>Avyanna: [dry] Not yet.</p>
<p>Elia: That&#x27;s the spirit.</p>
<hr>
<p>[Cinnamon&#x27;s text scrolls on the terminal above the galley counter.]</p>
<p>&lt;CINNAMON.EXE// STATUS: evidence archive stable | NOTE: hostile systems will attempt narrative repair | SUGGESTION: remain observant&gt;</p>
<p>Avyanna: Narrative repair.</p>
<p>Elia: [cheerful] That means they&#x27;re going to lie louder.</p>
<p>Rho: And send invoices for the privilege.</p>
<p>[Avyanna swallows.]</p>
<p>Avyanna: [quiet] And we keep receipts.</p>
<p>[Vesper isn&#x27;t here.]</p>
<p>[But the phrase feels like a rail anyway.]</p>
<p>Bubbles: Yes.</p>
<p>&lt;BUBBLES// OBSERVATION: trainee repeating doctrine without prompting | INFERENCE: internalization | CONFIDENCE: 0.83&gt;</p>
<p>[Avyanna finishes her toast.]</p>
<p>[She doesn&#x27;t thank anyone five times.]</p>
<p>[She doesn&#x27;t apologize for taking up a chair.]</p>
<p>[She just exists in the galley with the others, and the ship allows it like it&#x27;s always been the rule.]</p>
<p>[Avyanna takes her mug to the sink when she&#x27;s done, because the ship culture prefers it, not because she&#x27;s afraid of being punished.]</p>
<p>[She pauses with her hands in warm water, watching soap bubbles rise and pop.]</p>
<p>(Small things can be safe too.)</p>
<p>[She dries her hands and, without looking at anyone for permission, writes one line in her notebook:]</p>
<p>&gt; **OBSERVATION:** breakfast arrived without an invoice.</p>
<p>[Then she puts the notebook away and goes back to the table.]</p>
<p>[No one tells her she&#x27;s taking too long.]</p>
<p>[No one asks what she&#x27;s paying.]</p>
<p>[The ship hums like a city that expects its citizens to eat, to wash dishes, to exist-and refuses to make any of it a moral trial.]</p>
<p>[For now.]</p>
</div>

